# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: water-treatment-control
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The **activated sludge** **process** is a type of biological wastewater treatment process for treating sewage or industrial wastewaters using aeration and a biological floc composed of bacteria and protozoa.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] It is one of several biological wastewater treatment alternatives in secondary treatment, which deals with the removal of biodegradable organic matter and suspended solids.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] It uses air (or oxygen) and microorganisms to biologically oxidize organic pollutants, producing a waste sludge (or floc) containing the oxidized material.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The activated sludge process for removing carbonaceous pollution begins with an aeration tank where air (or oxygen) is injected into the waste water.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This is followed by a settling tank to allow the biological flocs (the sludge blanket) to settle, thus separating the biological sludge from the clear treated water.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Part of the waste sludge is recycled to the aeration tank and the remaining waste sludge is removed for further treatment and ultimate disposal.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Plant types include package plants, oxidation ditch, deep shaft/vertical treatment, surface-aerated basins, and sequencing batch reactors (SBRs).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Aeration methods include diffused aeration, surface aerators (cones) or, rarely, pure oxygen aeration.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Sludge bulking can occur which makes activated sludge difficult to settle and frequently has an adverse impact on final effluent quality.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Treating sludge bulking and managing the plant to avoid a recurrence requires skilled management and may require full-time staffing of a works to allow immediate intervention.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] A new development of the activated sludge process is the Nereda process which produces a granular sludge that settles very well.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The activated sludge process is a biological process used to oxidise carbonaceous biological matter, oxidising nitrogenous matter (mainly ammonium and nitrogen) in biological matter, and removing nutrients (nitrogen and phosphorus).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The process takes advantage of aerobic micro-organisms that can digest organic matter in sewage, and clump together by flocculation entrapping fine particulate matter as they do so.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] It thereby produces a liquid that is relatively free from suspended solids and organic material, and flocculated particles that will readily settle out and can be removed.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Treatment of nitrogenous or phosphorous matter comprises the addition of an anoxic compartment inside the aeration tank in order to perform the nitrification-denitrification process more efficiently.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] First, ammonia is oxidized to nitrite, which is then converted into nitrate in aerobic conditions (aeration compartment).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Facultative bacteria then reduce the nitrate to nitrogen gas in anoxic conditions (anoxic compartment).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Moreover, the organisms used for the phosphorus uptake (Polyphosphate Accumulating Organisms) are more efficient under anoxic conditions.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] These microorganisms accumulate large amounts of phosphates in their cells and are settled in the secondary clarifier.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The settled sludge is either disposed of as waste activated sludge or reused in the aeration tank as return activated sludge.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Some sludge must always be returned to the aeration tanks to maintain an adequate population of organisms.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The yield of PAOs (Polyphosphate Accumulating Organisms) is reduced between 70 and 80% under aerobic conditions.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Even though the phosphorus can be removed upstream of the aeration tank by chemical precipitation (adding metal ions such as: calcium, aluminum or iron), the biological phosphorus removal is more economic due to the saving of chemicals.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The process involves air or oxygen being introduced into a mixture of screened, and primary treated sewage or industrial wastewater (wastewater) combined with organisms to develop a biological floc which reduces the organic content of the sewage.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This material, which in healthy sludge is a brown floc, is largely composed of Saprotrophic bacteria but also has an important protozoan flora component mainly composed of amoebae, Spirotrichs, Peritrichs including Vorticellids and a range of other filter-feeding species.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Other important constituents include motile and sedentary Rotifers.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This material is often described as sewage fungus but true fungal communities are relatively uncommon.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The combination of wastewater and biological mass is commonly known as *mixed liquor*.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In all activated sludge plants, once the wastewater has received sufficient treatment, excess mixed liquor is discharged into settling tanks and the treated supernatant is run off to undergo further treatment before discharge.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Part of the settled material, the sludge, is returned to the head of the aeration system to re-seed the new wastewater entering the tank.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This fraction of the floc is called *return activated sludge* (R.A.S.).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The space required for a sewage treatment plant can be reduced by using a membrane bioreactor to remove some wastewater from the mixed liquor prior to treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This results in a more concentrated waste product that can then be treated using the activated sludge process.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Many sewage treatment plants use axial flow pumps to transfer nitrified mixed liquor from the aeration zone to the anoxic zone for denitrification.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] These pumps are often referred to as internal mixed liquor recycle pumps (IMLR pumps).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The raw sewage, the RAS, and the nitrified mixed liquor are mixed by submersible mixers in the anoxic zones in order to achieve denitrification.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Activated sludge is also the name given to the active biological material produced by activated sludge plants.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Excess sludge is called "surplus activated sludge" or "waste activated sludge" and is removed from the treatment process to keep "food to biomass" (F/M) ratio in balance (where biomass refers to the activated sludge).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This sewage sludge is usually mixed with primary sludge from the primary clarifiers and undergoes further sludge treatment for example by anaerobic digestion, followed by thickening, dewatering, composting and land application.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The amount of sewage sludge produced from the activated sludge process is directly proportional to the amount of wastewater treated.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The total sludge production consists of the sum of primary sludge from the primary sedimentation tanks as well as waste activated sludge from the bioreactors.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The activated sludge process produces about 70–100 grams per cubic metre (1.9–2.7 oz/cu yd) of waste activated sludge (that is grams of dry solids produced per cubic metre of wastewater treated).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] 80 grams per cubic metre (2.2 oz/cu yd) is regarded as being typical.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In addition, about 110–170 grams per cubic metre (3.0–4.6 oz/cu yd) of primary sludge is produced in the primary sedimentation tanks which most - but not all - of the activated sludge process configurations use.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In the reactor/aerator and clarifier system, the sludge blanket is measured from the bottom of the clarifier to the level of settled solids in the clarifier's water column; this, in large plants, can be done up to three times a day.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The SVI is the volume of settled sludge occupied by a given mass of dry sludge solids.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] It is calculated by dividing the volume of settled sludge in a mixed liquor sample, measured in milliliters per liter of sample (after 30 minutes of settling), by the MLSS (Mixed Liquor Suspended Solids), measured in grams per liter.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The MCRT is the total mass (in kilograms or pounds) of mixed liquor suspended solids in the aerator and clarifier divided by the mass flow rate (in kilograms/pounds per day) of mixed liquor suspended solids leaving as WAS and final effluent.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The F/M is the ratio of food fed to the microorganisms each day to the mass of microorganisms held under aeration.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Specifically, it is the amount of BOD fed to the aerator (in kilograms/pounds per day) divided by the amount (in kilograms or pounds) of Mixed Liquor Volatile Suspended Solids (MLVSS) under aeration.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Note: Some references use MLSS (Mixed Liquor Suspended Solids) for expedience, but MLVSS is considered more accurate for the measure of microorganisms.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Again, due to expedience, COD is generally used, in lieu of BOD, as BOD takes five days for results.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] To ensure good bacterial settlement and to avoid sedimentation problems caused by filamentous bacteria, plants using atmospheric air as an oxygen source should maintain a dissolved oxygen (DO) level of about 2 mg/L in the aeration tank.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In pure oxygen systems, DO levels are usually in the range of 4 to 10 mg/L.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Operators should monitor the tank for low DO bacteria, such as S. natans, type 1701 and H. hydrossis, which indicate low DO conditions by elevated effluent turbidity and dark activated sludge with foul odours.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Many plants have on-line monitoring equipment that continuously measures and records DO levels at specific points within the aeration tank.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] These on-line analysers send data to the SCADA system and allow automatic control of the aeration system to maintain a predetermined DO level.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Whether generated automatically or taken manually, regular monitoring is necessary to favour organisms that settle well rather than filaments.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] However, operating the aeration system involves finding a balance between sufficient oxygen for proper treatment and the energy cost, which represents approximately 90% of the total treatment cost.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Based on these control methods, the amount of settled solids in the mixed liquor can be varied by wasting activated sludge (WAS) or returning activated sludge (RAS).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The returning activated sludge is designed to recycle a portion of the activated sludge from the secondary clarifier back to the aeration tank.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] It usually includes a pump that draws the portion back.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The RAS line is designed considering the potential for clogging, settling, and other relatable issues that manage to impact the flow of the activated sludge back to the aeration tank.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This line must handle the required flow of the plant and has to be designed to minimize the risk of solids settling or accumulating.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Ammonium can have a toxic effect on aquatic organisms.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Nitrification also takes place in bodies of water, which leads to oxygen depletion.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Furthermore, nitrate and ammonium are eutrophying (fertilizing) nutrients that can impair water bodies.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] For these reasons, nitrification and, in many cases, nitrogen removal is necessary.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] a) Nitrification: Oxidation of ammonium nitrogen and organically bound nitrogen to nitrate.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Nitrification is very sensitive to inhibitors and can lead to a pH value in poorly buffered water.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Nitrification is associated with the production of acid (H+).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This puts a strain on the buffering capacity of the water or a pH value shift may occur, which impairs the process.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] b) Denitrification: Reduction of nitrate nitrogen to molecular nitrogen, which escapes from the wastewater into the atmosphere.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This step can be carried out by microorganisms commonly found in sewage treatment plants.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] However, these only use the nitrate as an electron acceptor if no dissolved oxygen is present.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In order for denitrification to take place in the activated sludge process, an electron source, a reductant, must therefore also be present that can reduce sufficient nitrate to N2.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] If there is too little substrate in the raw wastewater, this can be added artificially.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In addition, denitrification corrects the change in H+ concentration (pH value shift) that occurs during nitrification.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This is particularly important for poorly buffered water.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Nitrification and denitrification are in considerable contradiction with regard to the required environmental conditions.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Denitrification only takes place in the absence of dissolved oxygen and with a sufficient supply of oxidizable substances.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] There are a variety of types of activated sludge plants.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] There are a wide range of types of package plants, often serving small communities or industrial plants that may use hybrid treatment processes often involving the use of aerobic sludge to treat the incoming sewage.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In such plants the primary settlement stage of treatment may be omitted.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In these plants, a biotic floc is created which provides the required substrate.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Package plants are designed and fabricated by specialty engineering firms in dimensions that allow for their transportation to the job site in public highways, typically width and height of 3.7 by 3.7 metres (12 ft × 12 ft).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Length varies with capacity with larger plants being fabricated in pieces and welded on site.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Steel is preferred over synthetic materials (e.g., plastic) for its durability.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Package plants are commonly variants of extended aeration, to promote the "fit and forget" approach required for small communities without dedicated operational staff.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] There are various standards to assist with their design.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] To use less space, treat difficult waste, and intermittent flows, a number of designs of hybrid treatment plants have been produced.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Such plants often combine at least two stages of the three main treatment stages into one combined stage.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In the UK, where a large number of wastewater treatment plants serve small populations, package plants are a viable alternative to building a large structure for each process stage.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In the US, package plants are typically used in rural areas, highway rest stops and trailer parks.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Package plants may be referred to as *high charged* or *low charged*.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This refers to the way the biological load is processed.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In high charged systems, the biological stage is presented with a high organic load and the combined floc and organic material is then oxygenated for a few hours before being charged again with a new load.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In the low charged system the biological stage contains a low organic load and is combined with flocculate for longer times.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In some areas, where more land is available, sewage is treated in large round or oval ditches with one or more horizontal aerators typically called brush or disc aerators which drive the mixed liquor around the ditch and provide aeration.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] These are oxidation ditches, often referred to by manufacturer's trade names such as Pasveer, Orbal, or Carrousel.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] They have the advantage that they are relatively easy to maintain and are resilient to shock loads that often occur in smaller communities (i.e. at breakfast time and in the evening).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Oxidation ditches are installed commonly as 'fit & forget' technology, with typical design parameters of a hydraulic retention time of 24 – 48 hours, and a sludge age of 12 – 20 days.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This compares with nitrifying activated sludge plants having a retention time of 8 hours, and a sludge age of 8 – 12 days.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Where land is in short supply sewage may be treated by injection of oxygen into a pressured return sludge stream which is injected into the base of a deep columnar tank buried in the ground.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Such shafts may be up to 100 metres (330 ft) deep and are filled with sewage liquor.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] As the sewage rises the oxygen forced into solution by the pressure at the base of the shaft breaks out as molecular oxygen providing a highly efficient source of oxygen for the activated sludge biota.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The rising oxygen and injected return sludge provide the physical mechanism for mixing of the sewage and sludge.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Mixed sludge and sewage is decanted at the surface and separated into supernatant and sludge components.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The efficiency of deep shaft treatment can be high.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Surface aerators are commonly quoted as having an aeration efficiency of 0.5–1.5 kg O2/kWh (1.1–3.3 lb O2/kWh), diffused aeration as 1.5–2.5 kg O2/kWh (3.3–5.5 lb O2/kWh).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] However, the costs of construction are high.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Deep Shaft has seen the greatest uptake in Japan, because of the land area issues.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Deep Shaft was developed by ICI, as a spin-off from their Pruteen process.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] DeepShaft is a patented, licensed, process.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The licensee has changed several times and currently (2015) Noram Engineering sells it.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Most biological oxidation processes for treating industrial wastewaters have in common the use of oxygen (or air) and microbial action.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Surface-aerated basins achieve 80 to 90% removal of BOD with retention times of 1 to 10 days.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The basins may range in depth from 1.5 to 5.0 metres (4.9 to 16.4 ft) and utilize motor-driven aerators floating on the surface of the wastewater.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In an aerated basin system, the aerators provide two functions: they transfer air into the basins required by the biological oxidation reactions, and they provide the mixing required for dispersing the air and for contacting the reactants (that is, oxygen, wastewater and microbes).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Typically, the floating surface aerators are rated to deliver the amount of air equivalent to 1.8 to 2.7 kilograms O2/kWh (4.0 to 6.0 lb O2/kWh).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] However, they do not provide as good mixing as is normally achieved in activated sludge systems and therefore aerated basins do not achieve the same performance level as activated sludge units.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Biological oxidation processes are sensitive to temperature and, between 0 and 40 °C (32 and 104 °F), the rate of biological reactions increase with temperature.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Most surface aerated vessels operate at between 4 and 32 °C (39 and 90 °F).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Sequencing batch reactors (SBRs) treat wastewater in batches within the same vessel.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] This means that the bioreactor and final clarifier are not separated in space but in a timed sequence.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The installation consists of at least two identically equipped tanks with a common inlet, which can be alternated between them.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] While one tank is in settle/decant mode the other is aerating and filling.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Sewage liquor is run into deep tanks with diffuser grid aeration systems that are attached to the floor.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] These are like the diffused airstone used in tropical fish tanks but on a much larger scale.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Air is pumped through the blocks and the curtain of bubbles formed both oxygenates the liquor and also provides the necessary mixing action.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Where capacity is limited or the sewage is unusually strong or difficult to treat, oxygen may be used instead of air.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Typically, the air is generated by some type of air blower.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Vertically mounted tubes of up to 1-metre (3.3 ft) diameter extending from just above the base of a deep concrete tank to just below the surface of the sewage liquor.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] A typical shaft might be 10 metres (33 ft) high.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] At the surface end, the tube is formed into a cone with helical vanes attached to the inner surface.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] When the tube is rotated, the vanes spin liquor up and out of the cones drawing new sewage liquor from the base of the tank.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In many works, each cone is located in a separate cell that can be isolated from the remaining cells if required for maintenance.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Some works may have two cones to a cell and some large works may have 4 cones per cell.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Pure oxygen activated sludge aeration systems are sealed-tank reactor vessels with surface aerator type impellers mounted within the tanks at the oxygen carbon liquor surface interface.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The amount of oxygen entrainment, or DO (Dissolved Oxygen), can be controlled by a weir adjusted level control, and a vent gas oxygen controlled oxygen feed valve.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Oxygen is generated on site by cryogenic distillation of air, pressure swing adsorption, or other methods.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] These systems are used where wastewater plant space is at a premium and high sewage throughput is required as high energy costs are involved in purifying oxygen.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] A new development of the activated sludge process is the Nereda process which produces a granular sludge that settles very well (the sludge volume index is reduced from 200–300 to 40 millilitres per gram (192–288 to 38 US fl oz/oz)).
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] A new process reactor system is created to take advantage of this quick settling sludge and is integrated into the aeration tank instead of having a separate unit outside.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] As of 2015, about 30 Nereda wastewater treatment plants worldwide were operational, under construction or under design, varying in size from 5,000 up to 858,000 person equivalent.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The discharge of toxic industrial pollution to treatment plants designed primarily to treat domestic sewage can create process upsets.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The activated sludge process is an example for a more high-tech, energy intensive or "mechanized" process that is relatively expensive compared to some other wastewater treatment systems.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] It can provide a very high level of treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Activated sludge plants are wholly dependent on an electrical supply to power the aerators to transfer settled solids back to the aeration tank inlet, and in many cases to pump waste sludge and final effluent.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In some works untreated sewage is lifted by pumps to the head-works to provide sufficient fall through the works to enable a satisfactory discharge head for the final effluent.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Alternative technologies such as trickling filter treatment requires much less power and can operate on gravity alone.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] The activated sludge process was discovered in 1913 in the United Kingdom by two engineers, Edward Ardern and W.T.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Lockett, who were conducting research for the Manchester Corporation Rivers Department at Davyhulme Sewage Works.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In 1912, Gilbert Fowler, a scientist at the University of Manchester, observed experiments being conducted at the Lawrence Experiment Station at Massachusetts involving the aeration of sewage in a bottle that had been coated with algae.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Fowler's engineering colleagues, Ardern and Lockett, experimented on treating sewage in a draw-and-fill reactor, which produced a highly treated effluent.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] They aerated the waste-water continuously for about a month and were able to achieve a complete nitrification of the sample material.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Believing that the sludge had been activated (in a similar manner to activated carbon) the process was named *activated sludge*.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] Their results were published in their seminal 1914 paper, and the first full-scale continuous-flow system was installed at Worcester two years later.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] In the aftermath of the First World War the new treatment method spread rapidly, especially to the US, Denmark, Germany and Canada.
[src:water-treatment-control/activated-sludge] By the late 1930s, the activated sludge treatment became a well-known biological wastewater treatment process in those countries where sewer systems and sewage treatment plants were common.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] In water treatment, **coagulation** and flocculation involve the addition of compounds that promote the clumping of fine floc into larger floc so that they can be more easily separated from the water.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] Coagulation is a chemical process that involves neutralization of charge whereas flocculation is a physical process and does not involve neutralization of charge.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] The coagulation-flocculation process can be used as a preliminary or intermediary step between other water or wastewater treatment processes like filtration and sedimentation.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] Iron and aluminium salts are the most widely used coagulants but salts of other metals such as titanium and zirconium have been found to be highly effective as well.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] Coagulation is affected only by the type of coagulant used, its dose and mass; pH and initial turbidity of the water that is being treated; and properties of the pollutants present.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] The effectiveness of the coagulation process is also affected by pretreatments like oxidation.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] In a colloidal suspension, particles will settle very slowly or not at all because the colloidal particles carry surface electrical charges that mutually repel each other.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] This surface charge is most commonly evaluated in terms of zeta potential, the electrical potential at the slipping plane.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] To induce coagulation, a coagulant (typically a metallic salt) with the opposite charge is added to the water to overcome the repulsive charge and "destabilize" the suspension.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] For example, the colloidal particles are negatively charged and alum is added as a coagulant to create positively charged ions.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] Once the repulsive charges have been neutralized (since opposite charges attract), van der Waals force will cause the particles to cling together (agglomerate) and form micro floc.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] The dose of the coagulant to be used can be determined via the jar test.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] The jar test involves exposing same volume samples of the water to be treated to different doses of the coagulant and then simultaneously mixing the samples at a constant rapid mixing time.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] The microfloc formed after coagulation further undergoes flocculation and is allowed to settle.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] Then the turbidity of the samples is measured and the dose with the lowest turbidity can be said to be optimum.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] Despite its widespread use in the performance of so-called "dewatering experiments", the jar test is limited in its usefulness due to several disadvantages.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] For example, evaluating the performance of prospective coagulants or flocculants requires both significant volumes of water/wastewater samples (liters) and experimental time (hours).
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] This limits the scope of the experiments which can be conducted, including the addition of replicates.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] Furthermore, the analysis of jar test experiments produces results which are often only semi-quantitative.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] Coupled with the wide range of chemical coagulants and flocculants that exist, it has been remarked that determining the most appropriate dewatering agent as well as the optimal dose "is widely considered to be more of an ‘art’ rather than a ‘science’".
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] As such, dewatering performance tests such as the jar test lend themselves well to miniaturization.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] An automated device for determining the coagulant dose is the Streaming Current Detector (SCD).
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] The SCD measures the net surface charge of the particles and shows a streaming current value of 0 when the charges are neutralized (cationic coagulants neutralize the anionic colloids).
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] At this value (0), the coagulant dose can be said to be optimum.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] Coagulation itself results in the formation of floc but flocculation is required to help the floc further aggregate and settle.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] The coagulation-flocculation process itself removes only about 60%-70% of Natural Organic Matter (NOM) and thus, other processes like oxidation, filtration and sedimentation are necessary for complete raw water or wastewater treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/coagulation-water-treatment] Coagulant aids (polymers that bridge the colloids together) are also often used to increase the efficiency of the process.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] A **disinfectant** is a chemical substance or compound used to inactivate or destroy microorganisms on inert surfaces.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Disinfection does not necessarily kill all microorganisms, especially resistant bacterial spores; it is less effective than sterilization, which is an extreme physical or chemical process that kills all types of life.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Disinfectants are generally distinguished from other antimicrobial agents such as antibiotics, which destroy microorganisms within the body, and antiseptics, which destroy microorganisms on living tissue.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Disinfectants are also different from biocides.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Biocides are intended to destroy all forms of life, not just microorganisms, whereas disinfectants work by destroying the cell wall of microbes or interfering with their metabolism.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] It is also a form of decontamination, and can be defined as the process whereby physical or chemical methods are used to reduce the amount of pathogenic microorganisms on a surface.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Disinfectants can also be used to destroy microorganisms on the skin and mucous membrane, as in the medical dictionary historically the word simply meant that it destroys microbes.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Sanitizers are substances that simultaneously clean and disinfect.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Disinfectants kill more germs than sanitizers.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Disinfectants are frequently used in hospitals, dental surgeries, kitchens, and bathrooms to kill infectious organisms.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Sanitizers are mild compared to disinfectants and are used primarily to clean things that are in human contact, whereas disinfectants are concentrated and are used to clean surfaces like floors and building premises.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Bacterial endospores are most resistant to disinfectants, but some fungi, viruses and bacteria also possess some resistance.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] An alternative term used in the sanitation sector for disinfection of waste streams, sewage sludge or fecal sludge is **sanitisation** or **sanitization**.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The Australian Therapeutic Goods Order No.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] 54 defines several grades of disinfectant as will be used below.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] 2. when associated with the words "low", "intermediate" or "high" means "low", "intermediate" or "high" level disinfectant respectively.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] One way to compare disinfectants is to compare how well they do against a known disinfectant and rate them accordingly.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Phenol is the standard, and the corresponding rating system is called the "Phenol coefficient".
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The disinfectant to be tested is compared with phenol on a standard microbe (usually *Salmonella typhi* or *Staphylococcus aureus*).
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Disinfectants that are more effective than phenol have a coefficient > 1.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Those that are less effective have a coefficient < 1.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The standard European approach for disinfectant validation consists of a basic suspension test, a quantitative suspension test (with low and high levels of organic material added to act as 'interfering substances') and a two part simulated-use surface test.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] A less specific measurement of effectiveness is the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) classification into either *high*, *intermediate* or *low* levels of disinfection.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] "High-level disinfection kills all organisms, except high levels of bacterial spores" and is done with a chemical germicide marketed as a sterilant by the U.S.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] "Intermediate-level disinfection kills mycobacteria, most viruses, and bacteria with a chemical germicide registered as a 'tuberculocide' by the Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] An alternative assessment is to measure the Minimum inhibitory concentrations (MICs) of disinfectants against selected (and representative) microbial species, such as through the use of microbroth dilution testing.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] However, those methods are obtained at standard inoculum levels without considering the inoculum effect.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] More informative methods are nowadays in demand to determine the minimum disinfectant dose as a function of the density of the target microbial species.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] A perfect disinfectant would also offer complete and full microbiological sterilisation, without harming humans and useful form of life, be inexpensive, and noncorrosive.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] However, most disinfectants are also, by nature, potentially harmful (even toxic) to humans or animals.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Most modern household disinfectants contain denatonium, an exceptionally bitter substance added to discourage ingestion, as a safety measure.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Those that are used indoors should never be mixed with other cleaning products as chemical reactions can occur.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The choice of disinfectant to be used depends on the particular situation.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Some disinfectants have a wide spectrum (kill many different types of microorganisms), while others kill a smaller range of disease-causing organisms but are preferred for other properties (they may be non-corrosive, non-toxic, or inexpensive).
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] There are arguments for creating or maintaining conditions that are not conducive to bacterial survival and multiplication, rather than attempting to kill them with chemicals.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Bacteria can increase in number very quickly, which enables them to evolve rapidly.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Should some bacteria survive a chemical attack, they give rise to new generations composed completely of bacteria that have resistance to the particular chemical used.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Under a sustained chemical attack, the surviving bacteria in successive generations are increasingly resistant to the chemical used, and ultimately the chemical is rendered ineffective.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] For this reason, some question the wisdom of impregnating cloths, cutting boards and worktops in the home with bactericidal chemicals.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Air disinfectants are typically chemical substances capable of disinfecting microorganisms suspended in the air.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Disinfectants are generally assumed to be limited to use on surfaces, but that is not the case.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] In 1928, a study found that airborne microorganisms could be killed using mists of dilute bleach.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] An air disinfectant must be dispersed either as an aerosol or vapour at a sufficient concentration in the air to cause the number of viable infectious microorganisms to be significantly reduced.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] In the 1940s and early 1950s, further studies showed inactivation of diverse bacteria, influenza virus, and *Penicillium chrysogenum* (previously *P. notatum*) mold fungus using various glycols, principally propylene glycol and triethylene glycol.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] In principle, these chemical substances are ideal air disinfectants because they have both high lethality to microorganisms and low mammalian toxicity.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Although glycols are effective air disinfectants in controlled laboratory environments, it is more difficult to use them effectively in real-world environments because the disinfection of air is sensitive to continuous action.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Continuous action in real-world environments with outside air exchanges at door, HVAC, and window interfaces, and in the presence of materials that absorb and remove glycols from the air, poses engineering challenges that are not critical for surface disinfection.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The engineering challenge associated with creating a sufficient concentration of the glycol vapours in the air have not to date been sufficiently addressed.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Alcohol and alcohol plus Quaternary ammonium cation based compounds comprise a class of proven surface sanitizers and disinfectants approved by the EPA and the Centers for Disease Control for use as a hospital grade disinfectant.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Alcohols are most effective when combined with distilled water to facilitate diffusion through the cell membrane; 100% alcohol typically denatures only external membrane proteins.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] A mixture of 70% ethanol or isopropanol diluted in water is effective against a wide spectrum of bacteria, though higher concentrations are often needed to disinfect wet surfaces.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Additionally, high-concentration mixtures (such as 80% ethanol + 5% isopropanol) are required to effectively inactivate lipid-enveloped viruses (such as HIV, hepatitis B, and hepatitis C).
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The efficacy of alcohol is enhanced when in solution with the wetting agent dodecanoic acid (coconut soap).
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The synergistic effect of 29.4% ethanol with dodecanoic acid is effective against a broad spectrum of bacteria, fungi, and viruses.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Further testing is being performed against *Clostridioides difficile* (C.Diff) spores with higher concentrations of ethanol and dodecanoic acid, which proved effective with a contact time of ten minutes.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Aldehydes, such as formaldehyde and glutaraldehyde, have a wide microbicidal activity and are sporicidal and fungicidal.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] They are partly inactivated by organic matter and have slight residual activity.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Some bacteria have developed resistance to glutaraldehyde, and it has been found that glutaraldehyde can cause asthma and other health hazards, hence ortho-phthalaldehyde is replacing glutaraldehyde.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Oxidizing agents act by oxidizing the cell membrane of microorganisms, which results in a loss of structure and leads to cell lysis and death.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] A large number of disinfectants operate in this way.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Chlorine and oxygen are strong oxidizers, so their compounds figure heavily here.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Peroxycarboxylic acids and inorganic peroxo acids are strong oxidants and extremely effective disinfectants.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Phenolics are active ingredients in some household disinfectants.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] They are also found in some mouthwashes and in disinfectant soap and handwashes.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Quaternary ammonium compounds ("quats"), such as benzalkonium chloride, are a large group of related compounds.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Some concentrated formulations have been shown to be effective low-level disinfectants.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Quaternary ammonia at or above 200ppm plus alcohol solutions exhibit efficacy against difficult to kill non-enveloped viruses such as norovirus, rotavirus, or polio virus.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Newer synergous, low-alcohol formulations are highly effective broad-spectrum disinfectants with quick contact times (3–5 minutes) against bacteria, enveloped viruses, pathogenic fungi, and mycobacteria.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Quats are biocides that also kill algae and are used as an additive in large-scale industrial water systems to minimize undesired biological growth.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] This group comprises aqueous solution of chlorine, hypochlorite, or hypochlorous acid.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Occasionally, chlorine-releasing compounds and their salts are included in this group.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Frequently, a concentration of < 1 ppm of available chlorine is sufficient to kill bacteria and viruses, spores and mycobacteria requiring higher concentrations.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Chlorine has been used for applications, such as the deactivation of pathogens in drinking water, swimming pool water and wastewater, for the disinfection of household areas and for textile bleaching.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Most metals, especially those with high atomic weights can inhibit the growth of pathogens by disrupting their metabolism.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The biguanide polymer polyaminopropyl biguanide is specifically bactericidal at very low concentrations (10 mg/L).
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] It has a unique method of action: The polymer strands are incorporated into the bacterial cell wall, which disrupts the membrane and reduces its permeability, which has a lethal effect to bacteria.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] It is also known to bind to bacterial DNA, alter its transcription, and cause lethal DNA damage.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] It has very low toxicity to higher organisms such as human cells, which have more complex and protective membranes.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Common sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3) has antifungal properties, and some antiviral and antibacterial properties, though those are too weak to be effective at a home environment.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Ultraviolet germicidal irradiation is the use of high-intensity shortwave ultraviolet light for disinfecting smooth surfaces such as dental tools, but not porous materials that are opaque to the light such as wood or foam.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Ultraviolet light is also used for municipal water treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Ultraviolet light fixtures are often present in microbiology labs, and are activated only when there are no occupants in a room (e.g., at night).
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Heat treatment can be used for disinfection and sterilization.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The phrase "sunlight is the best disinfectant" was popularized in 1913 by United States Supreme Court Justice Louis Brandeis and later advocates of government transparency.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] While sunlight's ultraviolet rays can act as a disinfectant, the Earth's ozone layer blocks the rays' most effective wavelengths.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Ultraviolet light-emitting machines, such as those used to disinfect some hospital rooms, make for better disinfectants than sunlight.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Since the mid-1990s cold plasma has been shown to be an efficient sterilization/disinfection agent.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Cold plasma is an ionized gas that remains at room temperature.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] It generates reactive oxygen and reactive nitrogen species that interact with bacterial wall and membrane and cause oxidation of the lipids and proteins and can also lyse the cells.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Cold plasma can inactivate bacteria, viruses, and fungi.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] There has been a rise in the use of electrostatic disinfectants in recent years.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Electrostatic disinfection is a process achieved by use of electrostatic sprayers notable examples of which include the Vycel -Vycel 4 or the Techtronics Ryobi.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Electrostatic Sprayers are a new technology for disinfecting surfaces.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Unlike conventional spraying bottles or devices electrostatic sprayers apply a positive ionic charge to liquid disinfectants as they pass through the nozzle of the device.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The positively charged disinfectant distributed through the nozzle of an electrostatic sprayer is attracted to negatively charged surfaces, which allows for efficient coating of disinfectant solutions on to hard nonporous surfaces.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] There are a number of specific disinfectants designed for use with electrostatic sprayers and these are often dissolved in solution or diluted with water.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Notable disinfectant sprays that are designed for use with electrostatic sprayers include Citrox Disinfectant Solution and Vital Oxide Disinfectant Solution.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Individuals who work manufacturing disinfectants have higher exposure to the raw and harsh chemicals used in the production of disinfectants compared to the general population.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] This is due to the use of manual labor and automated machinery.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] However, the use of automated machinery does not dismiss any direct contact with the chemicals within the production of disinfectants.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Chemicals used in disinfectants vary in forms, such as gel, liquid, and powder.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Minimal information remains about the health and safety of workers in other sectors of the production and manufacturing process of disinfectants.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Inspection is a process of disinfectant manufacturing that only requires human intervention.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Many workers in the inspection phase of mass production of disinfectants have reported accidental inhalation of fumes, direct dermal contact, eye irritation, and accidental ingestion of disinfectant substances.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The chemicals, quaternary ammonium compounds (QACs), phenolic compounds, iodophors, glutaraldehyde, alcohols, and chlorine, were most associated with the previous health effects.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] This evidence of dermal exposure was associated with the misuse or lack of Personal Protective Equipment (PPE).
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Cancer has been shown to only develop in consistent exposure, along with the lack of use of Personal Protective Equipment (PPE).
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Among these numerous health effects, evidence showed that dermal exposure was more hazardous than inhalation.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] These health effects can be minimized with the implementation of guidelines from the CDC, NPIC, OSHA, and NIOSH.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] There is evidence that exposure to cleaning and disinfectant products can cause acute health effects on healthcare workers.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Observed effects include eye irritation and watery eyes, headaches, dizziness, throat irritation and wheezing, skin irritation, and work-related asthma.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Some chemicals in cleaning and disinfectants that have been associated with health impacts include chlorine, ammonia,[2] ethanolamine, 2-butoxyethanol, quaternary ammonium compounds (QACs), and bleach.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] The adverse health impacts of disinfectants are still not well studied, which makes it difficult to develop guidelines for use in healthcare settings that take mind of potential effects.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] There is also little information about how effective and safe alternative cleaning technology, so-called “green cleaning,” is.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] New guidelines would need to maintain high hygiene standards and prevent healthcare-associated infections.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Professional and Industrial cleaners, despite being essential in maintaining hygiene and safety are one of the understudied occupational groups.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Continuous exposure to cleaning agents containing ethanolamine, chloramine-T, and Quaternary Ammonium Compounds (QACs) was found to cause Occupational Asthma (OA) in cleaners.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] QAC was also found to be involved in developing antimicrobial resistance.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Symptoms reported were dyspnea, cough, and wheezing.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Females had more risk of acquiring OA due to higher exposures both at home and work.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Exposures happen through dermal contact, hand-to-mouth, and inhalation of aerosolized quats.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Researchers suggest continuous use of Personal Protective Equipment (PPE), periodic medical examinations, and guidelines on how to handle chemicals.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Dermal, respiratory, immune, reproductive, and developmental effects of exposure are investigated but there is a currently limited scope of this study.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Other concerns found were its impact on wastewater management, soil, and food especially in dissolved concentrations.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] In the United States, the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), and Food and Drug Administration (FDA) regulate QACs depending on their intended purposes.
[src:water-treatment-control/disinfection] Stricter regulations and policies are warranted for safer use and search for alternatives to limit exposures.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO retains the solute on the pressurized side of the membrane and the purified solvent passes to the other side.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The relative sizes of the various molecules determines what passes through.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] "Selective" membranes reject large molecules, while accepting smaller molecules (such as solvent molecules, e.g., water).
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Reverse osmosis is most commonly known for its use in drinking water purification from seawater, removing the salt and other effluent materials from the water molecules.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] As of 2013 the world's largest RO desalination plant was in Sorek, Israel, outputting 624 thousand cubic metres per day (165 million US gallons per day).
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO systems for private use are also available for purifying municipal tap water or pre-treated well water.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] A process of osmosis through semi-permeable membranes was first observed in 1748 by Jean-Antoine Nollet.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] For the following 200 years, osmosis was only a laboratory phenomenon.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] In 1950, the University of California at Los Angeles (UCLA) first investigated osmotic desalination.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Researchers at both UCLA and University of Florida desalinated seawater in the mid-1950s, but the flux was too low to be commercially viable.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Sidney Loeb at UCLA and Srinivasa Sourirajan at the National Research Council of Canada, Ottawa, found techniques for making asymmetric membranes characterized by an effectively thin "skin" layer supported atop a highly porous and much thicker substrate region.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] John Cadotte, of Filmtec corporation, discovered that membranes with particularly high flux and low salt passage could be made by interfacial polymerization of *m*-phenylene diamine and trimesoyl chloride.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Cadotte's patent on this process was the subject of litigation and expired.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Almost all commercial RO membrane is now made by this method.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] By 2019, approximately 16,000 desalination plants operated around the world, producing around 95 million cubic metres per day (25 billion US gallons per day).
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Around half of this capacity was in the Middle East and North Africa region.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] In 1977 Cape Coral, Florida became the first US municipality to use RO at scale, with an initial operating capacity of 11.35 million liters (3 million US gal) per day.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] By 1985, rapid growth led the city to operate the world's largest low-pressure RO plant, producing 56.8 million liters (15 million US gal) per day (MGD).
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] In (forward) osmosis, the solvent moves from an area of low solute concentration (high water potential), through a membrane, to an area of high solute concentration (low water potential).
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The driving force for the movement of the solvent is the reduction in the Gibbs free energy of the system in which the difference in solvent concentration between the sides of a membrane is reduced.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] It reduces as the solvent moves into the more concentrated solution.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Applying an external pressure to reverse the natural flow of pure solvent, thus, is reverse osmosis.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The process is similar to other membrane technology applications.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO differs from filtration in that the mechanism of fluid flow is reversed, as the solvent crosses membrane, leaving the solute behind.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The predominant removal mechanism in membrane filtration is straining, or size exclusion, where the pores are 0.01 micrometers or larger, so the process can theoretically achieve perfect efficiency regardless of parameters such as the solution's pressure and concentration.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO instead involves solvent diffusion across a membrane that is either nonporous or uses nanofiltration with pores 0.001 micrometers in size.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The predominant removal mechanism is from differences in solubility or diffusivity, and the process is dependent on pressure, solute concentration, and other conditions.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO requires pressure between 2–17 bar (30–250 psi) for fresh and brackish water, and 40–82 bar (600–1200 psi) for seawater.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Seawater has around 27 bar (390 psi) natural osmotic pressure that must be overcome.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] As for their energy consumption, seawater RO systems typically require 2.9-5.5 kWh/m3, although state-of-the-art systems are around 2.3 kWh/m3.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Membrane pore sizes vary from 0.1 to 5,000 nm.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Particle filtration removes particles of 1 μm or larger.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Microfiltration removes particles of 50 nm or larger.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Ultrafiltration removes particles of roughly 3 nm or larger.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Nanofiltration removes particles of 1 nm or larger.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO is in the final category of membrane filtration, hyperfiltration, and removes particles larger than ~0.2 nm.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Around the world, household drinking water purification systems, including an RO step, are commonly used for improving water for drinking and cooking.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] In some systems, the carbon prefilter is replaced by a cellulose triacetate (CTA) membrane.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] CTA is a paper by-product membrane bonded to a synthetic layer that allows contact with chlorine in the water.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] These require a small amount of chlorine in the water source to prevent bacteria from forming on it.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The typical rejection rate for CTA membranes is 85–95%.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The cellulose triacetate membrane rots unless protected by chlorinated water, while the thin-film composite membrane breaks down in the presence of chlorine.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The thin-film composite (TFC) membrane is made of synthetic material, and requires the chlorine to be removed before the water enters the membrane.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] To protect the TFC membrane elements from chlorine damage, carbon filters are used as pre-treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] TFC membranes have a higher rejection rate of 95–98% and a longer life than CTA membranes.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] To work effectively, the water feeding to these units should be under pressure (typically 280 kPa (40 psi) or greater).
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Though Portable RO Water Purifiers are commercially available and extensively used in areas lacking cleaning potable water, in Europe such processing of natural mineral water (as defined by a European directive) is not allowed.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] In practice, a fraction of the living bacteria pass through RO through membrane imperfections or bypass the membrane entirely through leaks in seals.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] A solar-powered desalination unit produces potable water from saline water by using a photovoltaic system to supply the energy.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Solar power works well for water purification in settings lacking grid electricity and can reduce operating costs and greenhouse emissions.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] For example, a solar-powered desalination unit designed passed tests in Australia's Northern Territory.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Sunlight's intermittent nature makes output prediction difficult without an energy storage capability.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] However batteries or thermal energy storage systems can provide power when the sun does not.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Larger scale reverse osmosis water purification units (ROWPU) exist for military use.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] These have been adopted by the United States armed forces and the Canadian Forces.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Some models are containerized, some are trailers, and some are themselves vehicles.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The water is treated with a polymer to initiate coagulation.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Next, it is run through a multi-media filter where it undergoes primary treatment, removing turbidity.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] It is then pumped through a cartridge filter which is usually spiral-wound cotton.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] This process strips any particles larger than 5 μm and eliminates almost all turbidity.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The clarified water is then fed through a high-pressure piston pump into a series of RO vessels.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] 90.00–99.98% of the raw water's total dissolved solids are removed and military standards require that the result have no more than 1000–1500 parts per million by measure of electrical conductivity.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO-purified rainwater collected from storm drains is used for landscape irrigation and industrial cooling in Los Angeles and other cities.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] In industry, RO removes minerals from boiler water at power plants.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The water is distilled multiple times to ensure that it does not leave deposits on the machinery or cause corrosion.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO is used to clean effluent and brackish groundwater.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The effluent in larger volumes (more than 500 m3/day) is treated in a water treatment plant first, and then the effluent runs through RO.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] This hybrid process reduces treatment cost significantly and lengthens membrane life.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO can be used for the production of deionized water.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] In 2002, Singapore announced that a process named NEWater would be a significant part of its water plans.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO would be used to treat wastewater before discharging the effluent into reservoirs.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Reverse osmosis is a more economical way to concentrate liquids (such as fruit juices) than conventional heat-treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Concentration of orange and tomato juice has advantages including a lower operating cost and the ability to avoid heat-treatment, which makes it suitable for heat-sensitive substances such as protein and enzymes.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO is used in the dairy industry to produce whey protein powders and concentrate milk.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The whey (liquid remaining after cheese manufacture) is concentrated with RO from 6% solids to 10–20% solids before ultrafiltration processing.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The retentate can then be used to make whey powders, including whey protein isolate.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Additionally, the permeate, which contains lactose, is concentrated by RO from 5% solids to 18–total solids to reduce crystallization and drying costs.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Although RO was once avoided in the wine industry, it is now widespread.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] An estimated 60 RO machines were in use in Bordeaux, France, in 2002.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Known users include many of elite firms, such as Château Léoville-Las Cases.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] In 1946, some maple syrup producers started using RO to remove water from sap before boiling the sap to syrup.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO allows about 75–90% of the water to be removed, reducing energy consumption and exposure of the syrup to high temperatures.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] When beer at typical concentration is subjected to reverse osmosis, both water and alcohol pass across the membrane more readily than other components, leaving a "beer concentrate".
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The concentrate is then diluted with fresh water to restore the non-volatile components to their original intensity.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] For small-scale hydrogen production, RO is sometimes used to prevent formation of mineral deposits on the surface of electrodes.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Many reef aquarium keepers use RO systems to make fish-friendly seawater.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Ordinary tap water can contain excessive chlorine, chloramines, copper, nitrates, nitrites, phosphates, silicates, or other chemicals detrimental to marine organisms.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Contaminants such as nitrogen and phosphates can lead to unwanted algae growth.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] An effective combination of both RO and deionization is popular among reef aquarium keepers, and is preferred above other water purification processes due to the low cost of ownership and operating costs.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Where chlorine and chloramines are found in the water, carbon filtration is needed before RO, as common residential membranes do not address these compounds.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Freshwater aquarists also use RO to duplicate the soft waters found in many tropical waters.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] While many tropical fish can survive in treated tap water, breeding can be impossible.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Many aquatic shops sell containers of RO water for this purpose.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] It is possible to produce RO water from a domestic supply.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Equipment is fairly simple to install, and works at regular domestic pressures.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The membranes in the RO filter cartridges lose their effectiveness over time, and need occasional replacement.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] An increasingly popular method of cleaning windows is the "water-fed pole" system.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Instead of washing windows with conventional detergent, they are scrubbed with purified water, typically containing less than 10 ppm dissolved solids, using a brush on the end of a pole wielded from ground level.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO is commonly used to purify the water.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Treatment with RO is limited, resulting in low recoveries on high concentration (measured with electrical conductivity) and membrane fouling.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO applicability is limited by conductivity, organics, and scaling inorganic elements such as CaSO4, Si, Fe and Ba.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Low organic scaling can use two different technologies: spiral wound membrane, and (for high organic scaling, high conductivity and higher pressure (up to 90 bars)), disc tube modules with RO membranes can be used.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Disc tube modules were redesigned for landfill leachate purification that is usually contaminated with organic material.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Due to the cross-flow, it is given a flow booster pump that recirculates the flow over the membrane between 1.5 and 3 times before it is released as a concentrate.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] High velocity protects against membrane scaling and allows membrane cleaning.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Areas that have limited surface water or groundwater may choose to desalinate.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO is an increasingly common method, because of its relatively low energy consumption.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Energy consumption is around 3 kWh/m3 (11,000 J/L), with the development of more efficient energy recovery devices and improved membrane materials.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] According to the International Desalination Association, for 2011, RO was used in 66% of installed desalination capacity (0.0445 of 0.0674 km3/day), and nearly all new plants.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Other plants use thermal distillation methods: multiple-effect distillation, and multi-stage flash.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Sea-water RO (SWRO) desalination requires around 3 kWh/m3, much higher than those required for other forms of water supply, including RO treatment of wastewater, at 0.1 to 1 kWh/m3.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Up to 50% of the seawater input can be recovered as fresh water, though lower recovery rates may reduce membrane fouling and energy consumption.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Brackish water reverse osmosis (BWRO) is the desalination of water with less salt than seawater, usually from river estuaries or saline wells.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The process is substantially the same as SWRO, but requires lower pressures and less energy.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Up to 80% of the feed water input can be recovered as fresh water, depending on feed salinity.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The Ashkelon desalination plant in Israel is the world's largest.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Pretreatment is important when working nanofiltration membranes due to their spiral-wound design.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The material is engineered to allow one-way flow.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The design does not allow for backpulsing with water or air agitation to scour its surface and remove accumulated solids.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Since material cannot be removed from the membrane surface, it is susceptible to fouling (loss of production capacity).
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Therefore, pretreatment is a necessity for any RO or nanofiltration system.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The high pressure pump pushes water through the membrane.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Typical pressures for brackish water range from 1.6 to 2.6 MPa (225 to 376 psi).
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] In the case of seawater, they range from 5.5 to 8 MPa (800 to 1,180 psi).
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Where energy recovery is used, part of the high pressure pump's work is done by the energy recovery device, reducing energy inputs.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The membrane assembly consists of a pressure vessel with a membrane that allows feedwater to be pushed against it.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The membrane must be strong enough to withstand the pressure.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO membranes are made in a variety of configurations.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The two most common are spiral-wound and hollow-fiber.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Only part of the water pumped onto the membrane passes through.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The left-behind "concentrate" passes along the saline side of the membrane and flushes away the salt and other remnants.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The percentage of desalinated water is the "recovery ratio".
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] This varies with salinity and system design parameters: typically 20% for small seawater systems, 40% – 50% for larger seawater systems, and 80% – 85% for brackish water.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The concentrate flow is typically 3 bar/50 psi less than the feed pressure, and thus retains much of the input energy.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The desalinated water purity is a function of the feed water salinity, membrane selection and recovery ratio.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] To achieve higher purity a second pass can be added which generally requires another pumping cycle.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Purity expressed as total dissolved solids typically varies from 100 to 400 parts per million (ppm or mg/litre) on a seawater feed.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] A level of 500 ppm is generally the upper limit for drinking water, while the US Food and Drug Administration classifies mineral water as water containing at least 250 ppm.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Energy recovery can reduce energy consumption by 50% or more.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Much of the input energy can be recovered from the concentrate flow, and the increasing efficiency of energy recovery devices greatly reduces energy requirements.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The desalinated water is stabilized to protect downstream pipelines and storage, usually by adding lime or caustic soda to prevent corrosion of concrete-lined surfaces.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Liming material is used to adjust pH between 6.8 and 8.1 to meet the potable water specifications, primarily for effective disinfection and for corrosion control.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Remineralisation may be needed to replace minerals removed from the water by desalination, although this process has proved to be costly and inconvenient in order to meet mineral demand by humans and plants as found in typical freshwater.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] For instance water from Israel's national water carrier typically contains dissolved magnesium levels of 20 to 25 mg/liter, while water from the Ashkelon plant has no magnesium.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Ashkelon water created magnesium-deficiency symptoms in crops, including tomatoes, basil, and flowers, and had to be remedied by fertilization.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Israeli drinking water standards require a minimum calcium level of 20 mg/liter.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Askelon's post-desalination treatment uses sulfuric acid to dissolve calcite (limestone), resulting in calcium concentrations of 40 to 46 mg/liter, lower than the 45 to 60 mg/liter found in typical Israeli fresh water.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Post-treatment disinfection provides secondary protection against compromised membranes and downstream problems.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Disinfection by means of ultraviolet (UV) lamps (sometimes called germicidal or bactericidal) may be employed to sterilize pathogens that evade the RO process.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Chlorination or chloramination (chlorine and ammonia) protects against pathogens that may have lodged in the distribution system downstream.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Large-scale industrial/municipal systems recover typically 75% to 80% of the feed water, or as high as 90%, because they can generate the required higher pressure.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Household RO units use a lot of water because they have low back pressure.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Household RO water purifiers typically produce one liter of usable water and 3-25 liters of wastewater.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The remainder is discharged, usually into the drain.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Because wastewater carries the rejected contaminants, recovering this water is not practical for household systems.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Wastewater is typically delivered to house drains.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] A RO unit delivering 20 liters (5.3 U.S. gal) of treated water per day also discharge between 50 and 80 liters (13 and 21 U.S. gal).
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] This led India's National Green Tribunal to propose a ban on RO water purification systems in areas where the total dissolved solids (TDS) measure in water is less than 500 mg/liter.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] In Delhi, large-scale use of household RO devices has increased the total water demand of the already water-parched National Capital Territory of India.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] RO removes both harmful contaminants and desirable minerals.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Some studies report some relation between long-term health effects and consumption of water low on calcium and magnesium, although these studies are of low quality.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Depending upon the desired product, either the solvent or solute stream of RO will be waste.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] For food concentration applications, the concentrated solute stream is the product and the solvent stream is waste.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] For water treatment applications, the solvent stream is purified water and the solute stream is concentrated waste.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The solvent waste stream from food processing may be used as reclaimed water, but there may be fewer options for disposal of a concentrated waste solute stream.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Ships may use marine dumping and coastal desalination plants typically use marine outfalls.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Landlocked RO plants may require evaporation ponds or injection wells to avoid polluting groundwater or surface runoff.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Current RO membranes, thin-film composite (TFC) polyamide membranes, are being studied to find ways of improving their permeability.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Through new imaging methods, researchers were able to make 3D models of membranes and examine how water flowed through them.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] They found that TFC membranes with areas of low flow significantly decreased water permeability.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] By ensuring uniformity of the membranes and allowing water to flow continuously without slowing down, membrane permeability could be improved 30–40%.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Research has examined integrating RO with electrodialysis to improve recovery of valuable deionized products, or to reduce concentrate volumes.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Another approach is low-pressure high-recovery multistage RO (LPHR).
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] It produces concentrated brine and freshwater by cycling the output repeatedly through a relatively porous membrane at relatively low pressure.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Each cycle removes additional impurities.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Once the output is relatively pure, it is sent through a conventional RO membrane at conventional pressure to complete the filtration step.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] LPHR was found to be economically feasible, recovering more than 70% with an OPD between 58 and 65 bar and leaving no more than 350 ppm TDS from a seawater feed with 35,000 ppm TDS.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Carbon nanotubes are meant to potentially solve the typical tradeoff between the permeability and the selectivity of RO membranes.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] CNTs present many ideal characteristics including: mechanical strength, electron affinity, and also exhibiting flexibility during modification.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] By restructuring carbon nanotubes and coating or impregnating them with other chemical compounds, scientists can manufacture these membranes to have all of the most desirable traits.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The hope with CNT membranes is to find a combination of high water permeability while also decreasing the amount of neutral solutes taken out of the water.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] This would help decrease energy costs and the cost of remineralization after purification through the membrane.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Graphene membranes are meant to take advantage of their thinness to increase efficiency.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Graphene is a singular layer of carbon atoms, so it is about 1000 times thinner than existing membranes.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Graphene membranes are around 100 nm thick while current membranes are about 100 μm.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Many researchers were concerned with the durability of graphene and if it would be able to handle RO pressures.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] New research finds that depending on the substrate (a supporting layer that does no filtration and only provides structural support), graphene membranes can withstand 57MPa of pressure which is about 10 times the typical pressures for seawater RO.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Batch RO may offer increased energy efficiency, more durable equipment and higher salinity limits.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The conventional approach claimed that molecules cross the membrane individually.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] A research team devised a "solution-friction" theory, claiming that molecules in groups through transient pores.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] Characterizing that process could guide membrane development.
[src:water-treatment-control/reverse-osmosis] The accepted theory is that individual water molecules diffuse through the membrane, termed the "solution-diffusion" model.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sewage treatment plants (STPs) come in many different sizes and process configurations.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] A large number of sewage treatment technologies have been developed, mostly using biological treatment processes.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Design engineers and decision makers need to take into account technical and economical criteria of each alternative when choosing a suitable technology.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Often, the main criteria for selection are desired effluent quality, expected construction and operating costs, availability of land, energy requirements and sustainability aspects.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In developing countries and in rural areas with low population densities, sewage is often treated by various on-site sanitation systems and not conveyed in sewers.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] These systems include septic tanks connected to drain fields, on-site sewage systems (OSS), and vermifilter systems.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] On the other hand, advanced and relatively expensive sewage treatment plants may include tertiary treatment with disinfection and possibly even a fourth treatment stage to remove micropollutants.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] At the global level, an estimated 52% of sewage is treated.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] However, sewage treatment rates are highly unequal for different countries around the world.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] For example, while high-income countries treat approximately 74% of their sewage, developing countries treat an average of just 4.2%.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The treatment of sewage is part of the field of sanitation.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sanitation also includes the management of human waste and solid waste as well as stormwater (drainage) management.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The term *sewage treatment plant* is often used interchangeably with the term *wastewater treatment plant*.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The term *sewage treatment plant* (STP) (or *sewage treatment works*) is nowadays often replaced with the term *wastewater treatment plant* (WWTP).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Strictly speaking, the latter is a broader term that can also refer to industrial wastewater treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The terms *water recycling center* or *water reclamation plants* are also in use as synonyms.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The overall aim of treating sewage is to produce an effluent that can be discharged to the environment while causing as little water pollution as possible, or to produce an effluent that can be reused in a useful manner.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This is achieved by removing contaminants from the sewage.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] With regards to biological treatment of sewage, the treatment objectives can include various degrees of the following: to transform or remove organic matter, nutrients (nitrogen and phosphorus), pathogenic organisms, and specific trace organic constituents (micropollutants).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Some types of sewage treatment produce sewage sludge which can be treated before safe disposal or reuse.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Under certain circumstances, the treated sewage sludge might be termed *biosolids* and can be used as a fertilizer.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] For high income countries, the "per person organic matter load" has been found to be approximately 60 gram of BOD per person per day.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This is called the population equivalent (PE) and is also used as a comparison parameter to express the strength of industrial wastewater compared to sewage.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sewerage (or sewage system) is the infrastructure that conveys sewage or surface runoff (stormwater, meltwater, rainwater) using sewers.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] It encompasses components such as receiving drains, manholes, pumping stations, storm overflows, and screening chambers of the combined sewer or sanitary sewer.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sewerage ends at the entry to a sewage treatment plant or at the point of discharge into the environment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] It is the system of pipes, chambers, manholes or inspection chamber, etc. that conveys the sewage or storm water.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In many cities, sewage (municipal wastewater or municipal sewage) is carried together with stormwater, in a combined sewer system, to a sewage treatment plant.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In some urban areas, sewage is carried separately in sanitary sewers and runoff from streets is carried in storm drains.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Access to these systems, for maintenance purposes, is typically through a manhole.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] During high precipitation periods a sewer system may experience a combined sewer overflow event or a sanitary sewer overflow event, which forces untreated sewage to flow directly to receiving waters.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This can pose a serious threat to public health and the surrounding environment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The system of sewers is called *sewerage* or *sewerage system* in British English and *sewage system* or *sewer system* in American English.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sewage can be treated close to where the sewage is created, which may be called a *decentralized system* or even an *on-site system* (on-site sewage facility, septic tanks, etc.).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Alternatively, sewage can be collected and transported by a network of pipes and pump stations to a municipal treatment plant.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This is called a *centralized system* (see also sewerage and pipes and infrastructure).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] A large number of sewage treatment technologies have been developed, mostly using biological treatment processes (see list of wastewater treatment technologies).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Very broadly, they can be grouped into high tech (high cost) versus low tech (low cost) options, although some technologies might fall into either category.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Other grouping classifications are *intensive* or *mechanized* systems (more compact, and frequently employing high tech options) versus *extensive* or *natural* or *nature-based* systems (usually using natural treatment processes and occupying larger areas) systems.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This classification may be sometimes oversimplified, because a treatment plant may involve a combination of processes, and the interpretation of the concepts of high tech and low tech, intensive and extensive, mechanized and natural processes may vary from place to place.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Examples for more low-tech, often less expensive sewage treatment systems are shown below.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Some of these systems do not provide a high level of treatment, or only treat part of the sewage (for example only the toilet wastewater), or they only provide pre-treatment, like septic tanks.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] On the other hand, some systems are capable of providing a good performance, satisfactory for several applications.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Many of these systems are based on natural treatment processes, requiring large areas, while others are more compact.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In most cases, they are used in rural areas or in small to medium-sized communities.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] For example, waste stabilization ponds are a low cost treatment option with practically no energy requirements but they require a lot of land.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Due to their technical simplicity, most of the savings (compared with high tech systems) are in terms of operation and maintenance costs.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Examples for more high-tech, intensive or mechanized, often relatively expensive sewage treatment systems are listed below.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Some of them are energy intensive as well.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Many of them provide a very high level of treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] For example, broadly speaking, the activated sludge process achieves a high effluent quality but is relatively expensive and energy intensive.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] There are other process options which may be classified as disposal options, although they can also be understood as basic treatment options.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] These include: Application of sludge, irrigation, soak pit, leach field, fish pond, floating plant pond, water disposal/groundwater recharge, surface disposal and storage.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The application of sewage to land is both: a type of treatment and a type of final disposal.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] It leads to groundwater recharge and/or to evapotranspiration.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Land application include slow-rate systems, rapid infiltration, subsurface infiltration, overland flow.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] It is done by flooding, furrows, sprinkler and dripping.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] It is a treatment/disposal system that requires a large amount of land per person.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The *per person organic matter load* is a parameter used in the design of sewage treatment plants.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This concept is known as population equivalent (PE).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The base value used for PE can vary from one country to another.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Commonly used definitions used worldwide are: 1 PE equates to 60 gram of BOD per person per day, and it also equals 200 liters of sewage per day.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This concept is also used as a comparison parameter to express the strength of industrial wastewater compared to sewage.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] When choosing a suitable sewage treatment process, decision makers need to take into account technical and economical criteria.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Therefore, each analysis is site-specific.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] A life cycle assessment (LCA) can be used, and criteria or weightings are attributed to the various aspects.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This makes the final decision subjective to some extent.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] A range of publications exist to help with technology selection.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In industrialized countries, the most important parameters in process selection are typically efficiency, reliability, and space requirements.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In developing countries, they might be different and the focus might be more on construction and operating costs as well as process simplicity.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Choosing the most suitable treatment process is complicated and requires expert inputs, often in the form of feasibility studies.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This is because the main important factors to be considered when evaluating and selecting sewage treatment processes are numerous.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Odors emitted by sewage treatment are typically an indication of an anaerobic or *septic* condition.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Early stages of processing will tend to produce foul-smelling gases, with hydrogen sulfide being most common in generating complaints.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Large process plants in urban areas will often treat the odors with carbon reactors, a contact media with bio-slimes, small doses of chlorine, or circulating fluids to biologically capture and metabolize the noxious gases.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Other methods of odor control exist, including addition of iron salts, hydrogen peroxide, calcium nitrate, etc. to manage hydrogen sulfide levels.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The energy requirements vary with type of treatment process as well as sewage strength.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] For example, constructed wetlands and stabilization ponds have low energy requirements.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In comparison, the activated sludge process has a high energy consumption because it includes an aeration step.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Some sewage treatment plants produce biogas from their sewage sludge treatment process by using a process called anaerobic digestion.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This process can produce enough energy to meet most of the energy needs of the sewage treatment plant itself.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] For activated sludge treatment plants in the United States, around 30 percent of the annual operating costs is usually required for energy.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Most of this electricity is used for aeration, pumping systems and equipment for the dewatering and drying of sewage sludge.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Advanced sewage treatment plants, e.g. for nutrient removal, require more energy than plants that only achieve primary or secondary treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Small rural plants using trickling filters may operate with no net energy requirements, the whole process being driven by gravitational flow, including tipping bucket flow distribution and the desludging of settlement tanks to drying beds.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This is usually only practical in hilly terrain and in areas where the treatment plant is relatively remote from housing because of the difficulty in managing odors.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In highly regulated developed countries, industrial wastewater usually receives at least pretreatment if not full treatment at the factories themselves to reduce the pollutant load, before discharge to the sewer.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The pretreatment has the following two main aims: Firstly, to prevent toxic or inhibitory compounds entering the biological stage of the sewage treatment plant and reduce its efficiency.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] And secondly to avoid toxic compounds from accumulating in the produced sewage sludge which would reduce its beneficial reuse options.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Some industrial wastewater may contain pollutants which cannot be removed by sewage treatment plants.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Also, variable flow of industrial waste associated with production cycles may upset the population dynamics of biological treatment units.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Urban residents in many parts of the world rely on on-site sanitation systems without sewers, such as septic tanks and pit latrines, and fecal sludge management in these cities is an enormous challenge.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] For sewage treatment the use of septic tanks and other on-site sewage facilities (OSSF) is widespread in some rural areas, for example serving up to 20 percent of the homes in the U.S.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sewage treatment often involves two main stages, called primary and secondary treatment, while advanced treatment also incorporates a tertiary treatment stage with polishing processes.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Different types of sewage treatment may utilize some or all of the process steps listed below.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Preliminary treatment (sometimes called pretreatment) removes coarse materials that can be easily collected from the raw sewage before they damage or clog the pumps and sewage lines of primary treatment clarifiers.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The influent in sewage water passes through a bar screen to remove all large objects like cans, rags, sticks, plastic packets, etc. carried in the sewage stream.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This is most commonly done with an automated mechanically raked bar screen in modern plants serving large populations, while in smaller or less modern plants, a manually cleaned screen may be used.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The raking action of a mechanical bar screen is typically paced according to the accumulation on the bar screens and/or flow rate.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The solids are collected and later disposed in a landfill, or incinerated.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Bar screens or mesh screens of varying sizes may be used to optimize solids removal.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] If gross solids are not removed, they become entrained in pipes and moving parts of the treatment plant, and can cause substantial damage and inefficiency in the process.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Grit consists of sand, gravel, rocks, and other heavy materials.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Preliminary treatment may include a sand or grit removal channel or chamber, where the velocity of the incoming sewage is reduced to allow the settlement of grit.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Grit removal is necessary to (1) reduce formation of deposits in primary sedimentation tanks, aeration tanks, anaerobic digesters, pipes, channels, etc.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] (2) reduce the frequency of tank cleaning caused by excessive accumulation of grit; and (3) protect moving mechanical equipment from abrasion and accompanying abnormal wear.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The removal of grit is essential for equipment with closely machined metal surfaces such as comminutors, fine screens, centrifuges, heat exchangers, and high pressure diaphragm pumps.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Grit chambers come in three types: horizontal grit chambers, aerated grit chambers, and vortex grit chambers.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Vortex grit chambers include mechanically induced vortex, hydraulically induced vortex, and multi-tray vortex separators.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Given that traditionally, grit removal systems have been designed to remove clean inorganic particles that are greater than 0.210 millimetres (0.0083 in), most of the finer grit passes through the grit removal flows under normal conditions.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] During periods of high flow deposited grit is resuspended and the quantity of grit reaching the treatment plant increases substantially.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Equalization basins can be used to achieve flow equalization.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This is especially useful for combined sewer systems which produce peak dry-weather flows or peak wet-weather flows that are much higher than the average flows.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Such basins can improve the performance of the biological treatment processes and the secondary clarifiers.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Disadvantages include the basins' capital cost and space requirements.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Flow equalization basins require variable discharge control, typically include provisions for bypass and cleaning, and may also include aerators and odor control.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In some larger plants, fat and grease are removed by passing the sewage through a small tank where skimmers collect the fat floating on the surface.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Air blowers in the base of the tank may also be used to help recover the fat as a froth.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Many plants, however, use primary clarifiers with mechanical surface skimmers for fat and grease removal.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Primary treatment is the "removal of a portion of the suspended solids and organic matter from the sewage".It consists of allowing sewage to pass slowly through a basin where heavy solids can settle to the bottom while oil, grease and lighter solids float to the surface and are skimmed off.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] These basins are called *primary sedimentation tanks* or *primary clarifiers* and typically have a hydraulic retention time (HRT) of 1.5 to 2.5 hours.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The settled and floating materials are removed and the remaining liquid may be discharged or subjected to secondary treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Primary settling tanks are usually equipped with mechanically driven scrapers that continually drive the collected sludge towards a hopper in the base of the tank where it is pumped to sludge treatment facilities.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sewage treatment plants that are connected to a combined sewer system sometimes have a bypass arrangement after the primary treatment unit.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This means that during very heavy rainfall events, the secondary and tertiary treatment systems can be bypassed to protect them from hydraulic overloading, and the mixture of sewage and storm-water receives primary treatment only.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Primary sedimentation tanks remove about 50–70% of the suspended solids, and 25–40% of the biological oxygen demand (BOD).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The main processes involved in secondary sewage treatment are designed to remove as much of the dissolved solid material as possible.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] They use biological processes to digest and remove the remaining soluble material, especially the organic fraction.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This can be done with either suspended-growth or biofilm processes.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The microorganisms that feed on the organic matter present in the sewage grow and multiply, constituting the biological solids, or biomass.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] These grow and group together in the form of flocs or biofilms and, in some specific processes, as granules.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The biological floc or biofilm and remaining fine solids form a sludge which can be settled and separated.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] After separation, a liquid remains that is almost free of solids, and with a greatly reduced concentration of pollutants.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] A percentage of the settled/separated bio-solids are reintroduced at the influent to the secondary process as innoculant.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Secondary treatment can reduce organic matter (measured as biological oxygen demand (BOD), chemical oxygen demand (COD), etc ) from sewage, using aerobic or anaerobic processes.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The organisms involved in these processes are sensitive to the presence of toxic materials, although these are not expected to be present at high concentrations in typical municipal sewage.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Advanced sewage treatment generally involves three main stages, called primary, secondary and tertiary treatment but may also include intermediate stages and final polishing processes.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The purpose of tertiary treatment (also called *advanced treatment*) is to provide a final treatment stage to further improve the effluent quality before it is discharged to the receiving water body or reused.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] More than one tertiary treatment process may be used at any treatment plant.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] If disinfection is practiced, it is always the final process.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Tertiary treatment may include biological nutrient removal (alternatively, this can be classified as secondary treatment), disinfection and partly removal of micropollutants, such as environmental persistent pharmaceutical pollutants.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Tertiary treatment is sometimes defined as anything more than primary and secondary treatment in order to allow discharge into a highly sensitive or fragile ecosystem such as estuaries, low-flow rivers or coral reefs.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Treated water is sometimes disinfected chemically or physically (for example, by lagoons and microfiltration) prior to discharge into a stream, river, bay, lagoon or wetland, or it can be used for the irrigation of a golf course, greenway or park.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] If it is sufficiently clean, it can also be used for groundwater recharge or agricultural purposes.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sand filtration removes much of the residual suspended matter.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Filtration over activated carbon, also called *carbon adsorption,* removes residual toxins.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Micro filtration or synthetic membranes are used in membrane bioreactors and can also remove pathogens.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Settlement and further biological improvement of treated sewage may be achieved through storage in large human-made ponds or lagoons.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] These lagoons are highly aerobic, and colonization by native macrophytes, especially reeds, is often encouraged.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Disinfection of treated sewage aims to kill pathogens (disease-causing microorganisms) prior to disposal.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] It is increasingly effective after more elements of the foregoing treatment sequence have been completed.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The purpose of disinfection in the treatment of sewage is to substantially reduce the number of pathogens in the water to be discharged back into the environment or to be reused.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The target level of reduction of biological contaminants like pathogens is often regulated by the presiding governmental authority.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The effectiveness of disinfection depends on the quality of the water being treated (e.g. turbidity, pH, etc.), the type of disinfection being used, the disinfectant dosage (concentration and time), and other environmental variables.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Water with high turbidity will be treated less successfully, since solid matter can shield organisms, especially from ultraviolet light or if contact times are low.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Generally, short contact times, low doses and high flows all militate against effective disinfection.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Common methods of disinfection include ozone, chlorine, ultraviolet light, or sodium hypochlorite.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Monochloramine, which is used for drinking water, is not used in the treatment of sewage because of its persistence.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Chlorination remains the most common form of treated sewage disinfection in many countries due to its low cost and long-term history of effectiveness.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] One disadvantage is that chlorination of residual organic material can generate chlorinated-organic compounds that may be carcinogenic or harmful to the environment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Residual chlorine or chloramines may also be capable of chlorinating organic material in the natural aquatic environment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Further, because residual chlorine is toxic to aquatic species, the treated effluent must also be chemically dechlorinated, adding to the complexity and cost of treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Ultraviolet (UV) light can be used instead of chlorine, iodine, or other chemicals.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Because no chemicals are used, the treated water has no adverse effect on organisms that later consume it, as may be the case with other methods.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] UV radiation causes damage to the genetic structure of bacteria, viruses, and other pathogens, making them incapable of reproduction.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In many countries, UV light is becoming the most common means of disinfection because of the concerns about the impacts of chlorine in chlorinating residual organics in the treated sewage and in chlorinating organics in the receiving water.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] As with UV treatment, heat sterilization also does not add chemicals to the water being treated.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] However, unlike UV, heat can penetrate liquids that are not transparent.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Heat disinfection can also penetrate solid materials within wastewater, sterilizing their contents.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Thermal effluent decontamination systems provide low resource, low maintenance effluent decontamination once installed.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Ozone (O3) is generated by passing oxygen (O2) through a high voltage potential resulting in a third oxygen atom becoming attached and forming O3.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Ozone is very unstable and reactive and oxidizes most organic material it comes in contact with, thereby destroying many pathogenic microorganisms.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Ozone is considered to be safer than chlorine because, unlike chlorine which has to be stored on site (highly poisonous in the event of an accidental release), ozone is generated on-site as needed from the oxygen in the ambient air.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Ozonation also produces fewer disinfection by-products than chlorination.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] A disadvantage of ozone disinfection is the high cost of the ozone generation equipment and the requirements for special operators.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Ozone sewage treatment requires the use of an ozone generator, which decontaminates the water as ozone bubbles percolate through the tank.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Membranes can also be effective disinfectants, because they act as barriers, avoiding the passage of the microorganisms.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] As a result, the final effluent may be devoid of pathogenic organisms, depending on the type of membrane used.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This principle is applied in membrane bioreactors.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sewage may contain high levels of the nutrients nitrogen and phosphorus.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Typical values for nutrient loads per person and nutrient concentrations in raw sewage in developing countries have been published as follows: 8 g/person/d for total nitrogen (45 mg/L), 4.5 g/person/d for ammonia-N (25 mg/L) and 1.0 g/person/d for total phosphorus (7 mg/L).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The typical ranges for these values are: 6–10 g/person/d for total nitrogen (35–60 mg/L), 3.5–6 g/person/d for ammonia-N (20–35 mg/L) and 0.7–2.5 g/person/d for total phosphorus (4–15 mg/L).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Excessive release to the environment can lead to nutrient pollution, which can manifest itself in eutrophication.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This process can lead to algal blooms, a rapid growth, and later decay, in the population of algae.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In addition to causing deoxygenation, some algal species produce toxins that contaminate drinking water supplies.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Ammonia nitrogen, in the form of free ammonia (NH3) is toxic to fish.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Ammonia nitrogen, when converted to nitrite and further to nitrate in a water body, in the process of nitrification, is associated with the consumption of dissolved oxygen.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Nitrite and nitrate may also have public health significance if concentrations are high in drinking water, because of a disease called methemoglobinemia.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Phosphorus removal is important as phosphorus is a limiting nutrient for algae growth in many fresh water systems.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Therefore, an excess of phosphorus can lead to eutrophication.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] It is also particularly important for water reuse systems where high phosphorus concentrations may lead to fouling of downstream equipment such as reverse osmosis.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] A range of treatment processes are available to remove nitrogen and phosphorus.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Biological nutrient removal (BNR) is regarded by some as a type of secondary treatment process, and by others as a *tertiary* (or *advanced*) treatment process.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Nitrogen is removed through the biological oxidation of nitrogen from ammonia to nitrate (nitrification), followed by denitrification, the reduction of nitrate to nitrogen gas.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Nitrogen gas is released to the atmosphere and thus removed from the water.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Nitrification itself is a two-step aerobic process, each step facilitated by a different type of bacteria.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The oxidation of ammonia (NH3) to nitrite (NO2−) is most often facilitated by bacteria such as *Nitrosomonas* spp.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] (*nitroso* refers to the formation of a nitroso functional group).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Nitrite oxidation to nitrate (NO3−), though traditionally believed to be facilitated by *Nitrobacter* spp.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] (nitro referring the formation of a nitro functional group), is now known to be facilitated in the environment predominantly by *Nitrospira* spp.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Denitrification requires anoxic conditions to encourage the appropriate biological communities to form.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] *Anoxic conditions* refers to a situation where oxygen is absent but nitrate is present.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Denitrification is facilitated by a wide diversity of bacteria.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The activated sludge process, sand filters, waste stabilization ponds, constructed wetlands and other processes can all be used to reduce nitrogen.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Since denitrification is the reduction of nitrate to dinitrogen (molecular nitrogen) gas, an electron donor is needed.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This can be, depending on the wastewater, organic matter (from the sewage itself), sulfide, or an added donor like methanol.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The sludge in the anoxic tanks (denitrification tanks) must be mixed well (mixture of recirculated mixed liquor, return activated sludge, and raw influent) e.g. by using submersible mixers in order to achieve the desired denitrification.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Over time, different treatment configurations for activated sludge processes have evolved to achieve high levels of nitrogen removal.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] An initial scheme was called the Ludzack–Ettinger Process.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] It could not achieve a high level of denitrification.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The Modified Ludzak–Ettinger Process (MLE) came later and was an improvement on the original concept.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] It recycles mixed liquor from the discharge end of the aeration tank to the head of the anoxic tank.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This provides nitrate for the facultative bacteria.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] There are other process configurations, such as variations of the Bardenpho process.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] They might differ in the placement of anoxic tanks, e.g. before and after the aeration tanks.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Studies of United States sewage in the late 1960s estimated mean per capita contributions of 500 grams (18 oz) in urine and feces, 1,000 grams (35 oz) in synthetic detergents, and lesser variable amounts used as corrosion and scale control chemicals in water supplies.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Source control via alternative detergent formulations has subsequently reduced the largest contribution, but naturally the phosphorus content of urine and feces remained unchanged.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Phosphorus can be removed biologically in a process called enhanced biological phosphorus removal.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In this process, specific bacteria, called polyphosphate-accumulating organisms (PAOs), are selectively enriched and accumulate large quantities of phosphorus within their cells (up to 20 percent of their mass).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Phosphorus removal can also be achieved by chemical precipitation, usually with salts of iron (e.g. ferric chloride) or aluminum (e.g. alum), or lime.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This may lead to a higher sludge production as hydroxides precipitate and the added chemicals can be expensive.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Chemical phosphorus removal requires significantly smaller equipment footprint than biological removal, is easier to operate and is often more reliable than biological phosphorus removal.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Another method for phosphorus removal is to use granular laterite or zeolite.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Some systems use both biological phosphorus removal and chemical phosphorus removal.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The chemical phosphorus removal in those systems may be used as a backup system, for use when the biological phosphorus removal is not removing enough phosphorus, or may be used continuously.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In either case, using both biological and chemical phosphorus removal has the advantage of not increasing sludge production as much as chemical phosphorus removal on its own, with the disadvantage of the increased initial cost associated with installing two different systems.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Once removed, phosphorus, in the form of a phosphate-rich sewage sludge, may be sent to landfill or used as fertilizer in admixture with other digested sewage sludges.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In the latter case, the treated sewage sludge is also sometimes referred to as biosolids.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] 22% of the world's phosphorus needs could be satisfied by recycling residential wastewater.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Although concentrations of those substances and their decomposition products are quite low, there is still a chance of harming aquatic organisms.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] For pharmaceuticals, the following substances have been identified as toxicologically relevant: substances with endocrine disrupting effects, genotoxic substances and substances that enhance the development of bacterial resistances.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] They mainly belong to the group of EPPP.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Techniques for elimination of micropollutants via a fourth treatment stage during sewage treatment are implemented in Germany, Switzerland, Sweden and the Netherlands and tests are ongoing in several other countries.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In Switzerland it has been enshrined in law since 2016.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Since 1 January 2025, there has been a recast of the Urban Waste Water Treatment Directive in the European Union.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Due to the large number of amendments that have now been made, the directive was rewritten on 27 November 2024 as Directive (EU) 2024/3019, published in the EU Official Journal on 12 December, and entered into force on 1 January 2025.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The member states now have 31 months, i.e. until 31 July 2027, to adapt their national legislation to the new directive ("implementation of the directive").
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The amendment stipulates that, in addition to stricter discharge values for nitrogen and phosphorus, persistent trace substances must at least be partially separated.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The target, similar to Switzerland, is that 80% of 6 key substances out of 12 must be removed between discharge into the sewage treatment plant and discharge into the water body.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In addition, the municipal wastewater treatment sector is to be energy neutral by 2045 and the emission of microplastics and PFAS is to be monitored.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The implementation of the framework guidelines is staggered until 2045, depending on the size of the sewage treatment plant and its population equivalents (PE).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sewage treatment plants with over 150,000 PE have priority and should be adapted immediately, as a significant proportion of the pollution comes from them.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The latter concerns waters with a low dilution ratio, waters from which drinking water is obtained and those that are coastal waters, or those used as bathing waters or used for mussel farming.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Member States will be given the option not to apply fourth treatment in these areas if a risk assessment shows that there is no potential risk from micropollutants to human health and/or the environment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Such process steps mainly consist of activated carbon filters that adsorb the micropollutants.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The combination of advanced oxidation with ozone followed by granular activated carbon (GAC) has been suggested as a cost-effective treatment combination for pharmaceutical residues.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] For a full reduction of microplasts the combination of ultrafiltration followed by GAC has been suggested.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Also the use of enzymes such as laccase secreted by fungi is under investigation.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Microbial biofuel cells are investigated for their property to treat organic matter in sewage.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] To reduce pharmaceuticals in water bodies, source control measures are also under investigation, such as innovations in drug development or more responsible handling of drugs.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In the US, the National Take Back Initiative is a voluntary program with the general public, encouraging people to return excess or expired drugs, and avoid flushing them to the sewage system.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sewage sludge treatment describes the processes used to manage and dispose of sewage sludge produced during sewage treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sludge treatment is focused on reducing sludge weight and volume to reduce transportation and disposal costs, and on reducing potential health risks of disposal options.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Water removal is the primary means of weight and volume reduction, while pathogen destruction is frequently accomplished through heating during thermophilic digestion, composting, or incineration.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The choice of a sludge treatment method depends on the volume of sludge generated, and comparison of treatment costs required for available disposal options.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Air-drying and composting may be attractive to rural communities, while limited land availability may make aerobic digestion and mechanical dewatering preferable for cities, and economies of scale may encourage energy recovery alternatives in metropolitan areas.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sludge is mostly water with some amounts of solid material removed from liquid sewage.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Primary sludge includes settleable solids removed during primary treatment in primary clarifiers.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Secondary sludge is sludge separated in secondary clarifiers that are used in secondary treatment bioreactors or processes using inorganic oxidizing agents.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In intensive sewage treatment processes, the sludge produced needs to be removed from the liquid line on a continuous basis because the volumes of the tanks in the liquid line have insufficient volume to store sludge.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This is done in order to keep the treatment processes compact and in balance (production of sludge approximately equal to the removal of sludge).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The sludge removed from the liquid line goes to the sludge treatment line.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Aerobic processes (such as the activated sludge process) tend to produce more sludge compared with anaerobic processes.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] On the other hand, in extensive (natural) treatment processes, such as ponds and constructed wetlands, the produced sludge remains accumulated in the treatment units (liquid line) and is only removed after several years of operation.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sludge treatment options depend on the amount of solids generated and other site-specific conditions.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Composting is most often applied to small-scale plants with aerobic digestion for mid-sized operations, and anaerobic digestion for the larger-scale operations.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The sludge is sometimes passed through a so-called pre-thickener which de-waters the sludge.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Types of pre-thickeners include centrifugal sludge thickeners, rotary drum sludge thickeners and belt filter presses.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Dewatered sludge may be incinerated or transported offsite for disposal in a landfill or use as an agricultural soil amendment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Sewage treatment plants can have significant effects on the biotic status of receiving waters and can cause some water pollution, especially if the treatment process used is only basic.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] For example, for sewage treatment plants without nutrient removal, eutrophication of receiving water bodies can be a problem.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Water pollution (or aquatic pollution) is the contamination of water bodies, which has a negative impact on how they can be used.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] It is usually caused by human activities.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Water bodies include lakes, rivers, oceans, aquifers, reservoirs and groundwater.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Water pollution results when contaminants mix with these water bodies.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Contaminants can come from one of four main sources.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] These are sewage discharges, industrial activities, agricultural activities, and urban runoff including stormwater.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Water pollution may affect either surface water or groundwater.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This form of pollution can lead to many problems.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] One is the degradation of aquatic ecosystems.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Another is spreading water-borne diseases when people use polluted water for drinking or irrigation.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Water pollution also reduces the ecosystem services such as drinking water provided by the water resource.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] In 2024, The Royal Academy of Engineering released a study into the effects wastewater on public health in the United Kingdom.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The study gained media attention, with comments from the UKs leading health professionals, including Sir Chris Whitty.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Outlining 15 recommendations for various UK bodies to dramatically reduce public health risks by increasing the water quality in its waterways, such as rivers and lakes.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] After the release of the report, The Guardian newspaper interviewed Whitty, who stated that improving water quality and sewage treatment should be a high level of importance and a "public health priority".
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] He compared it to eradicating cholera in the 19th century in the country following improvements to the sewage treatment network.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] The study also identified that low water flows in rivers saw high concentration levels of sewage, as well as times of flooding or heavy rainfall.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] While heavy rainfall had always been associated with sewage overflows into streams and rivers, the British media went as far to warn parents of the dangers of paddling in shallow rivers during warm weather.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Whitty's comments came after the study revealed that the UK was experiencing a growth in the number of people that were using coastal and inland waters recreationally.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] This could be connected to a growing interest in activities such as open water swimming or other water sports.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Despite this growth in recreation, poor water quality meant some were becoming unwell during events.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p01] Most notably, the 2024 Paris Olympics had to delay numerous swimming-focused events like the triathlon due to high levels of sewage in the River Seine.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Increasingly, people use treated or even untreated sewage for irrigation to produce crops.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Cities provide lucrative markets for fresh produce, so are attractive to farmers.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Because agriculture has to compete for increasingly scarce water resources with industry and municipal users, there is often no alternative for farmers but to use water polluted with sewage directly to water their crops.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] There can be significant health hazards related to using water loaded with pathogens in this way.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] The World Health Organization developed guidelines for safe use of wastewater in 2006.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] They advocate a 'multiple-barrier' approach to wastewater use, where farmers are encouraged to adopt various risk-reducing behaviors.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Water reclamation is the process of converting municipal wastewater or sewage and industrial wastewater into water that can be reused for a variety of purposes.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] It is also called wastewater reuse, water reuse or water recycling.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] It is possible to reuse water in this way in cities or for irrigation in agriculture.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Other types of reuse are environmental reuse, industrial reuse, and reuse for drinking water, whether planned or not.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Reuse may include irrigation of gardens and agricultural fields or replenishing surface water and groundwater.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] This latter is also known as groundwater recharge.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Reused water also serve various needs in residences such as toilet flushing, businesses, and industry.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] It is possible to treat wastewater to reach drinking water standards.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Injecting reclaimed water into the water supply distribution system is known as direct potable reuse.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Drinking reclaimed water is not typical.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Reusing treated municipal wastewater for irrigation is a long-established practice.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] This is especially so in arid countries.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Reusing wastewater as part of sustainable water management allows water to remain an alternative water source for human activities.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] It also eases pressures on groundwater and other natural water bodies.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Before the 20th century in Europe, sewers usually discharged into a body of water such as a river, lake, or ocean.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] There was no treatment, so the breakdown of the human waste was left to the ecosystem.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] This could lead to satisfactory results if the assimilative capacity of the ecosystem is sufficient which is nowadays not often the case due to increasing population density.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Today, the situation in urban areas of industrialized countries is usually that sewers route their contents to a sewage treatment plant rather than directly to a body of water.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] In many developing countries, however, the bulk of municipal and industrial wastewater is discharged to rivers and the ocean without any treatment or after preliminary treatment or primary treatment only.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Few reliable figures exist on the share of the wastewater collected in sewers that is being treated worldwide.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] A global estimate by UNDP and UN-Habitat in 2010 was that 90% of all wastewater generated is released into the environment untreated.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] A more recent study in 2021 estimated that globally, about 52% of sewage is treated.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] As of 2022, without sufficient treatment, more than 80% of all wastewater generated globally is released into the environment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] High-income nations treat, on average, 70% of the wastewater they produce, according to UN Water.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Only 8% of wastewater produced in low-income nations receives any sort of treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] The Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply and Sanitation by WHO and UNICEF report in 2021 that 82% of people with sewer connections are connected to sewage treatment plants providing at least secondary treatment.However, this value varies widely between regions.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] For example, in Europe, North America, Northern Africa and Western Asia, a total of 31 countries had universal (>99%) wastewater treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] However, in Albania, Bermuda, North Macedonia and Serbia "less than 50% of sewered wastewater received secondary or better treatment" and in Algeria, Lebanon and Libya the value was less than 20% of sewered wastewater that was being treated.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] The report also found that "globally, 594 million people have sewer connections that don't receive sufficient treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Many more are connected to wastewater treatment plants that do not provide effective treatment or comply with effluent requirements.".
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] It is anticipated that wastewater production would rise by 24% by 2030 and by 51% by 2050.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Data in 2020 showed that there is still too much uncollected household wastewater: Only 66% of all household wastewater flows were collected at treatment facilities in 2020 (this is determined from data from 128 countries).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Based on data from 42 countries in 2015, the report stated that "32 per cent of all wastewater flows generated from point sources received at least some treatment".
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] For sewage that has indeed been collected at centralized sewage treatment plants, about 79% went on to be safely treated in 2020.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] It was not until the late 19th century that it became possible to treat the sewage by biologically decomposing the organic components through the use of microorganisms and removing the pollutants.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Land treatment was also steadily becoming less feasible, as cities grew and the volume of sewage produced could no longer be absorbed by the farmland on the outskirts.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] This established the then revolutionary possibility of biological treatment of sewage using a contact bed to oxidize the waste.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] ...in all probability the true way of purifying sewage...will be first to separate the sludge, and then turn into neutral effluent... retain it for a sufficient period, during which time it should be fully aerated, and finally discharge it into the stream in a purified condition.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] This is indeed what is aimed at and imperfectly accomplished on a sewage farm.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] From 1885 to 1891, filters working on Dibdin's principle were constructed throughout the UK and the idea was also taken up in the US at the Lawrence Experiment Station in Massachusetts, where Frankland's work was confirmed.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] In 1890, the LES developed a 'trickling filter' that gave a much more reliable performance.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] In most countries, sewage collection and treatment are subject to local and national regulations and standards.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] In the European Union, 0.8% of total energy consumption goes to wastewater treatment facilities.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] The European Union needs to make extra investments of €90 billion in the water and waste sector to meet its 2030 climate and energy goals.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] In October 2021, British Members of Parliament voted to continue allowing untreated sewage from combined sewer overflows to be released into waterways.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] In India, wastewater treatment regulations come under three central institutions, the ministries of forest, climate change housing, urban affairs and water.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] The various water and sanitation policies such as the "National Environment Policy 2006" and "National Sanitation Policy 2008" also lay down wastewater treatment regulations.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] State governments and local municipalities hold responsibility for the disposal of sewage and construction and maintenance of "sewerage infrastructure".
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Their efforts are supported by schemes offered by the Government of India, such as the National River Conservation Plan, Jawaharlal Nehru National Urban Renewal Mission, National Lake Conservation Plan.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Through the Ministry of Environment and Forest, India's government also has set up incentives that encourage industries to establish "common facilities" to undertake the treatment of wastewater.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] The 'Delhi Jal Board' (DJB) is currently operating on the construction of the largest sewage treatment plant in India.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] It will be operational by the end of 2022 with an estimated capacity of 564 MLD.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] It is supposed to solve the existing situation wherein untreated sewage water is being discharged directly into the river 'Yamuna'.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Currently, Japan's methods of wastewater treatment include rural community sewers, wastewater facilities, and on-site treatment systems such as the Johkasou system to treat domestic wastewater.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Larger wastewater facilities and sewer systems are generally used to treat wastewater in more urban areas with a larger population.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Rural sewage systems are used to treat wastewater at smaller domestic wastewater treatment plants for a smaller population.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Johkasou systems are on-site wastewater treatment systems tanks.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] They are used to treat the wastewater of a single household or to treat the wastewater of a small number of buildings in a more decentralized manner than a sewer system.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] In Libya, municipal wastewater treatment is managed by the general company for water and wastewater in Libya, which falls within the competence of the Housing and Utilities Government Ministry.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] There are approximately 200 sewage treatment plants across the nation, but few plants are functioning.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] In fact, the 36 larger plants are in the major cities; however, only nine of them are operational, and the rest of them are under repair.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] The largest operating wastewater treatment plants are situated in Sirte, Tripoli, and Misurata, with a design capacity of 21,000, 110,000, and 24,000 m3/day, respectively.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Moreover, a majority of the remaining wastewater facilities are small and medium-sized plants with a design capacity of approximately 370 to 6700 m3/day.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Therefore, 145,800 m3/day or 11 percent of the wastewater is actually treated, and the remaining others are released into the ocean and artificial lagoons although they are untreated.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] In fact, nonoperational wastewater treatment plants in Tripoli lead to a spill of over 1,275, 000 cubic meters of unprocessed water into the ocean every day.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and state environmental agencies set wastewater standards under the Clean Water Act.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Point sources must obtain surface water discharge permits through the National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System (NPDES).
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] Point sources include industrial facilities, municipal governments (sewage treatment plants and storm sewer systems), other government facilities such as military bases, and some agricultural facilities, such as animal feedlots.
[src:water-treatment-control/sewage-treatment-p02] EPA sets basic national wastewater standards: The "Secondary Treatment Regulation" applies to municipal sewage treatment plants, and the "Effluent guidelines" which are regulations for categories of industrial facilities.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Water purification can reduce the concentration of particulate matter including suspended particles, parasites, bacteria, algae, viruses, and fungi as well as reduce the concentration of a range of dissolved and particulate matter.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The standards for drinking water quality are typically set by governments or by international standards.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] These standards usually include minimum and maximum concentrations of contaminants, depending on the intended use of the water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] A visual inspection cannot determine if water is of appropriate quality.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Simple procedures such as boiling or the use of a household point of use water filter (typically with activated carbon) are not sufficient for treating all possible contaminants that may be present in water from an unknown source.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Even natural spring water—considered safe for all practical purposes in the 19th century—must now be tested before determining what kind of treatment, if any, is needed.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Chemical and microbiological analysis, while expensive, are the only way to obtain the information necessary for deciding on the appropriate method of purification.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The water emerging from some deep ground water may have fallen as rain many tens, hundreds, or thousands of years ago.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] , or may be extracted from boreholes or wells.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] content of this water to make it acceptable for drinking, cooking, and laundry use.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] is practised (a process in which river water is injected into an aquifer to store the water in times of plenty so that it is available in times of drought), the groundwater may require additional treatment depending on applicable state and federal regulations.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Typically located in the headwaters of river systems, upland reservoirs are usually sited above any human habitation and may be surrounded by a protective zone to restrict the opportunities for contamination.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Low land surface waters will have a significant bacterial load and may also contain algae, suspended solids and a variety of dissolved constituents.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] A new technology that can provide high quality drinking water by extracting water from the air by cooling the air and thus condensing water vapour.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Water collected from the atmosphere can be used especially in areas with significant dry seasons and in areas which experience fog even when there is little rain.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Freshwater bodies that are open to the atmosphere and are not designated as groundwater are termed surface waters.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The goals of the treatment are to remove unwanted constituents in the water and to make it safe to drink or fit for a specific purpose in industry or medical applications.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Widely varied techniques are available to remove contaminants like fine solids, micro-organisms and some dissolved inorganic and organic materials, or environmental persistent pharmaceutical pollutants.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The choice of method will depend on the quality of the water being treated, the cost of the treatment process and the quality standards expected of the processed water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The processes below are the ones commonly used in water purification plants.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Some or most may not be used depending on the scale of the plant and quality of the raw (source) water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The majority of water must be pumped from its source or directed into pipes or holding tanks.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] To avoid adding contaminants to the water, this physical infrastructure must be made from appropriate materials and constructed so that accidental contamination does not occur.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The first step in purifying surface water is to remove large debris such as sticks, leaves, rubbish and other large particles which may interfere with subsequent purification steps.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Most deep groundwater does not need screening before other purification steps.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] for periods between a few days and many months to allow natural biological purification to take place.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In many plants the incoming water was chlorinated to minimise the growth of fouling organisms on the pipe-work and tanks.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Because of the potential adverse quality effects (see chlorine below), this has largely been discontinued.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Pure water has a pH close to 7 (neither alkaline nor acidic).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Sea water can have pH values that range from 7.5 to 8.4 (moderately alkaline).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Fresh water can have widely ranging pH values depending on the geology of the drainage basin or aquifer and the influence of contaminant inputs (acid rain).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] If the water is acidic (lower than 7), lime, soda ash, or caustic soda (sodium hydroxide) can be added to raise the pH during water purification processes and is especially common practice for water softening.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The choice of chemical used for raising the pH often depends on the carbonate alkalinity in the water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Addition of such chemicals increases the carbonate ion concentration, forcing precipitation of calcium carbonate, and magnesium carbonate at even higher pH.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Ultimately, the water hardness is reduced.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] For highly acidic waters, forced draft degasifiers can be an effective way to raise the pH, by stripping dissolved carbon dioxide from the water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Making the water alkaline helps coagulation and flocculation processes work effectively and also helps to minimise the risk of lead being dissolved from lead pipes and from lead solder in pipe fittings.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Sufficient alkalinity also reduces the corrosiveness of water to iron pipes.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Acid (carbonic acid, hydrochloric acid or sulfuric acid) may be added to alkaline waters in some circumstances to lower the pH.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Alkaline water (above pH 7.0) does not necessarily mean that lead or copper from the plumbing system will not be dissolved into the water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The ability of water to precipitate calcium carbonate to protect metal surfaces and reduce the likelihood of toxic metals being dissolved in water is a function of pH, mineral content, temperature, alkalinity and calcium concentration.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] One of the first steps in most conventional water purification processes is the addition of chemicals to assist in the removal of particles suspended in water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Particles can be inorganic such as clay and silt or organic such as algae, bacteria, viruses, protozoa and natural organic matter.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Inorganic and organic particles contribute to the turbidity and colour of water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The addition of inorganic coagulants such as aluminium sulfate (or alum) or iron (III) salts such as iron(III) chloride cause several simultaneous chemical and physical interactions on and among the particles.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Within seconds, negative charges on the particles are neutralised by inorganic coagulants.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Also within seconds, metal hydroxide precipitates of the iron and aluminium ions begin to form.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] These precipitates combine into larger particles under natural processes such as Brownian motion and through induced mixing which is sometimes referred to as flocculation.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Amorphous metal hydroxides are known as "floc".
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Large, amorphous aluminium and iron (III) hydroxides adsorb and enmesh particles in suspension and facilitate the removal of particles by subsequent processes of sedimentation and filtration.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Aluminum hydroxides are formed within a fairly narrow pH range, typically: 5.5 to about 7.7.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Iron (III) hydroxides can form over a larger pH range including pH levels lower than are effective for alum, typically: 5.0 to 8.5.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In the literature, there is much debate and confusion over the usage of the terms coagulation and flocculation: Where does coagulation end and flocculation begin?
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In fact, coagulation and flocculation processes are ongoing once the metal salt coagulants are added.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Organic polymers were developed in the 1960s as aids to coagulants and, in some cases, as replacements for the inorganic metal salt coagulants.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Synthetic organic polymers are high molecular weight compounds that carry negative, positive or neutral charges.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] When organic polymers are added to water with particulates, the high molecular weight compounds adsorb onto particle surfaces and through interparticle bridging coalesce with other particles to form floc.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] PolyDADMAC is a popular cationic (positively charged) organic polymer used in water purification plants.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Waters exiting the flocculation basin may enter the sedimentation basin, also called a clarifier or settling basin.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] It is a large tank with low water velocities, allowing floc to settle to the bottom.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The sedimentation basin is best located close to the flocculation basin so the transit between the two processes does not permit settlement or floc break up.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Sedimentation basins may be rectangular, where water flows from end to end, or circular where flow is from the centre outward.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Sedimentation basin outflow is typically over a weir so only a thin top layer of water—that furthest from the sludge—exits.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In 1904, Allen Hazen showed that the efficiency of a sedimentation process was a function of the particle settling velocity, the flow through the tank and the surface area of tank.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Sedimentation tanks are typically designed within a range of overflow rates of 0.5 to 1.0 gallons per minute per square foot (or 1250 to 2500 litres per square meter per hour).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In general, sedimentation basin efficiency is not a function of detention time or depth of the basin.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Although, basin depth must be sufficient so that water currents do not disturb the sludge and settled particle interactions are promoted.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] As particle concentrations in the settled water increase near the sludge surface on the bottom of the tank, settling velocities can increase due to collisions and agglomeration of particles.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Typical detention times for sedimentation vary from 1.5 to 4 hours and basin depths vary from 10 to 15 feet (3 to 4.5 meters).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Lamella clarifiers, inclined flat plates or tubes can be added to traditional sedimentation basins to improve particle removal performance.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Inclined plates and tubes drastically increase the surface area available for particles to be removed in concert with Hazen's original theory.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The amount of ground surface area occupied by a sedimentation basin with inclined plates or tubes can be far smaller than a conventional sedimentation basin.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] As particles settle to the bottom of a sedimentation basin, a layer of sludge is formed on the floor of the tank which must be removed and treated.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The amount of sludge generated is significant, often 3 to 5 per cent of the total volume of water to be treated.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The cost of treating and disposing of the sludge can impact the operating cost of a water treatment plant.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The sedimentation basin may be equipped with mechanical cleaning devices that continually clean its bottom, or the basin can be periodically taken out of service and cleaned manually.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] A subcategory of sedimentation is the removal of particulates by entrapment in a layer of suspended floc as the water is forced upward.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The major advantage of floc blanket clarifiers is that they occupy a smaller footprint than conventional sedimentation.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The disadvantages are that particle removal efficiency can be highly variable depending on changes in influent water quality and influent water flow rate.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] When particles to be removed do not settle out of solution easily, dissolved air flotation (DAF) is often used.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] After coagulation and flocculation processes, water flows to DAF tanks where air diffusers on the tank bottom create fine bubbles that attach to the floc resulting in a floating mass of concentrated floc.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The floating floc blanket is removed from the surface and clarified water is withdrawn from the bottom of the DAF tank.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Water supplies that are particularly vulnerable to unicellular algae blooms and supplies with low turbidity and high colour often employ DAF.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] After separating most floc, the water is filtered as the final step to remove remaining suspended particles and unsettled floc.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The most common type of filter is a rapid sand filter.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Water moves vertically downward through sand which often has a layer of activated carbon or anthracite coal above the sand.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The top layer removes organic compounds, which contribute to taste and odour.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The space between sand particles is larger than the smallest suspended particles, so simple filtration is not enough.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Most particles pass through surface layers but are trapped in pore spaces or adhere to sand particles.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Effective filtration extends into the depth of the filter.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This property of the filter is key to its operation: if the top layer of sand were to block all the particles, the filter would quickly clog.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] To clean the filter, water is passed quickly upward through the filter, opposite the normal direction (called *backflushing* or *backwashing*) to remove embedded or unwanted particles.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Prior to this step, compressed air may be blown up through the bottom of the filter to break up the compacted filter media to aid the backwashing process; this is known as *air scouring*.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This contaminated water can be disposed of, along with the sludge from the sedimentation basin, or it can be recycled by mixing with the raw water entering the plant although this is often considered poor practice since it re-introduces an elevated concentration of bacteria into the raw water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Some water treatment plants employ pressure filters.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] These work on the same principle as rapid gravity filters, differing in that the filter medium is enclosed in a steel vessel and the water is forced through it under pressure.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Slow sand filters may be used where there is sufficient land and space, as the water flows very slowly through the filters.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] These filters rely on biological treatment processes for their action rather than physical filtration.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] They are carefully constructed using graded layers of sand, with the coarsest sand, along with some gravel, at the bottom and the finest sand at the top.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Drains at the base convey treated water away for disinfection.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Filtration depends on the development of a thin biological layer, called the zoogleal layer or Schmutzdecke, on the surface of the filter.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] An effective slow sand filter may remain in service for many weeks or even months, if the pretreatment is well designed, and produces water with a very low available nutrient level which physical methods of treatment rarely achieve.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Very low nutrient levels allow water to be safely sent through distribution systems with very low disinfectant levels, thereby reducing consumer irritation over offensive levels of chlorine and chlorine by-products.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Slow sand filters are not backwashed; they are maintained by having the top layer of sand scraped off when the flow is eventually obstructed by biological growth.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In bank filtration, natural sediments in a riverbank are used to provide the first stage of contaminant filtration.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] While typically not clean enough to be used directly for drinking water, the water gained from the associated extraction wells is much less problematic than river water taken directly from the river.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Membrane filters are widely used for filtering both drinking water and sewage.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] They are widely used in industry, particularly for beverage preparation (including bottled water).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] However no filtration can remove substances that are actually dissolved in the water such as phosphates, nitrates and heavy metal ions.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Ultrafiltration membranes use polymer membranes with chemically formed microscopic pores that can be used to filter out dissolved substances avoiding the use of coagulants.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The type of membrane media determines how much pressure is needed to drive the water through and what sizes of micro-organisms can be filtered out.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Ion exchange: Ion-exchange systems use ion-exchange resin- or zeolite-packed columns to replace unwanted ions.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The most common case is water softening consisting of removal of Ca2+ and Mg2+ ions replacing them with benign (soap friendly) Na+ or K+ ions.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Ion-exchange resins are also used to remove toxic ions such as nitrite, lead, mercury, arsenic and many others.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Precipitative softening: Water rich in hardness (calcium and magnesium ions) is treated with lime (calcium oxide) and/or soda-ash (sodium carbonate) to precipitate calcium carbonate out of solution utilising the common-ion effect.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Electrodeionization: Water is passed between a positive electrode and a negative electrode.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Ion-exchange membranes allow only positive ions to migrate from the treated water toward the negative electrode and only negative ions toward the positive electrode.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] High purity deionised water is produced continuously, similar to ion-exchange treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Complete removal of ions from water is possible if the right conditions are met.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The water is normally pre-treated with a reverse osmosis unit to remove non-ionic organic contaminants, and with gas transfer membranes to remove carbon dioxide.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] A water recovery of 99% is possible if the concentrate stream is fed to the RO inlet.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Disinfection is accomplished both by filtering out harmful micro-organisms and by adding disinfectant chemicals.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Water is disinfected to kill any pathogens which pass through the filters and to provide a residual dose of disinfectant to kill or inactivate potentially harmful micro-organisms in the storage and distribution systems.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Possible pathogens include viruses, bacteria, including *Salmonella*, *Cholera*, *Campylobacter* and *Shigella*, and protozoa, including *Giardia lamblia* and other *cryptosporidia*.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] After the introduction of any chemical disinfecting agent, the water is usually held in temporary storage – often called a contact tank or clear well – to allow the disinfecting action to complete.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The most common disinfection method involves some form of chlorine or its compounds such as chloramine or chlorine dioxide.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Chlorine is a strong oxidant that rapidly kills many harmful micro-organisms.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Because chlorine is a toxic gas, there is a danger of a release associated with its use.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This problem is avoided by the use of sodium hypochlorite, which is a relatively inexpensive solution used in household bleach that releases free chlorine when dissolved in water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Chlorine solutions can be generated on site by electrolyzing common salt solutions.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] A solid form, calcium hypochlorite, releases chlorine on contact with water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Handling the solid, however, requires more routine human contact through opening bags and pouring than the use of gas cylinders or bleach, which are more easily automated.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The generation of liquid sodium hypochlorite is inexpensive and also safer than the use of gas or solid chlorine.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Chlorine levels up to 4 milligrams per litre (4 parts per million) are considered safe in drinking water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] All forms of chlorine are widely used, despite their respective drawbacks.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] One drawback is that chlorine from any source reacts with natural organic compounds in the water to form potentially harmful chemical by-products.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] These by-products, trihalomethanes (THMs) and haloacetic acids (HAAs), are both carcinogenic in large quantities and are regulated by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and the Drinking Water Inspectorate in the UK.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The formation of THMs and haloacetic acids may be minimised by the effective removal of as many organics from the water as possible prior to chlorine addition.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Although chlorine is effective in killing bacteria, it has limited effectiveness against pathogenic protozoa that form cysts in water such as *Giardia lamblia* and *Cryptosporidium*.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Chlorine dioxide is a faster-acting disinfectant than elemental chlorine.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] It is relatively rarely used because in some circumstances it may create excessive amounts of chlorite, which is a by-product regulated to low allowable levels in the United States.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Chlorine dioxide can be supplied as an aqueous solution and added to water to avoid gas handling problems; chlorine dioxide gas accumulations may spontaneously detonate.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The use of chloramine is becoming more common as a disinfectant.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Although chloramine is not as strong an oxidant, it provides a longer-lasting residual than free chlorine because of its lower redox potential compared to free chlorine.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] It also does not readily form THMs or haloacetic acids (disinfection byproducts).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] It is possible to convert chlorine to chloramine by adding ammonia to the water after adding chlorine.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The chlorine and ammonia react to form chloramine.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Water distribution systems disinfected with chloramines may experience nitrification, as ammonia is a nutrient for bacterial growth, with nitrates being generated as a by-product.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Ozone is an unstable molecule which readily gives up one atom of oxygen providing a powerful oxidising agent which is toxic to most waterborne organisms.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] It is a very strong, broad spectrum disinfectant that is widely used in Europe and in a few municipalities in the United States and Canada.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Ozone disinfection, or ozonation, is an effective method to inactivate harmful protozoa that form cysts.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] It also works well against almost all other pathogens.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Ozone is made by passing oxygen through ultraviolet light or a "cold" electrical discharge.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] To use ozone as a disinfectant, it must be created on-site and added to the water by bubble contact.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Some of the advantages of ozone include the production of fewer dangerous by-products and the absence of taste and odour problems (in comparison to chlorination).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In the absence of a residual disinfectant in the water, chlorine or chloramine may be added throughout a distribution system to remove any potential pathogens in the distribution piping.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Ozone has been used in drinking water plants since 1906 where the first industrial ozonation plant was built in Nice, France.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Food and Drug Administration has accepted ozone as being safe; and it is applied as an anti-microbiological agent for the treatment, storage, and processing of foods.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] However, although fewer by-products are formed by ozonation, it has been discovered that ozone reacts with bromide ions in water to produce concentrations of the suspected carcinogen bromate.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Bromide can be found in fresh water supplies in sufficient concentrations to produce (after ozonation) more than 10 parts per billion (ppb) of bromate—the maximum contaminant level established by the USEPA.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Ozone disinfection is also energy intensive.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Ultraviolet light (UV) is very effective at inactivating cysts, in low turbidity water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] UV light's disinfection effectiveness decreases as turbidity increases, a result of the absorption, scattering, and shadowing caused by the suspended solids.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The main disadvantage to the use of UV radiation is that, like ozone treatment, it leaves no residual disinfectant in the water; therefore, it is sometimes necessary to add a residual disinfectant after the primary disinfection process.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This is often done through the addition of chloramines, discussed above as a primary disinfectant.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] When used in this manner, chloramines provide an effective residual disinfectant with very few of the negative effects of chlorination.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Over 2 million people in 28 developing countries use solar disinfection for daily drinking water treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Like UV, ionizing radiation (X-rays, gamma rays, and electron beams) has been used to sterilise water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Bromine and iodine can also be used as disinfectants.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] However, chlorine in water is over three times more effective as a disinfectant against *Escherichia coli* than an equivalent concentration of bromine, and over six times more effective than an equivalent concentration of iodine.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Iodine is commonly used for portable water purification, and bromine is common as a swimming pool disinfectant.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Portable water purification devices and methods are available for disinfection and treatment in emergencies or in remote locations.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Disinfection is the primary goal, since aesthetic considerations such as taste, odour, appearance, and trace chemical contamination do not affect the short-term safety of drinking water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Fluoride is usually added after the disinfection process.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] which decomposes in water, yielding fluoride ions.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This is a method of reducing the effects of hard water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In water systems subject to heating hardness salts can be deposited as the decomposition of bicarbonate ions creates carbonate ions that precipitate out of solution.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] , producing calcium carbonate of very high purity.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Several other methods of industrial and residential water treatment are claimed (without general scientific acceptance) to include the use of magnetic and/or electrical fields reducing the effects of hard water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] rocks), the water may be capable of dissolving lead from any lead pipes that it is carried in.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] slightly both assist in greatly reducing plumbo-solvency by creating insoluble lead salts on the inner surfaces of the pipes.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Radium can be removed by ion exchange, or by water conditioning.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Although fluoride is added to water in many areas, some areas of the world have excessive levels of natural fluoride in the source water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] or cause undesirable cosmetic effects such as staining of teeth.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Other popular methods for purifying water, especially for local private supplies are listed below.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In some countries some of these methods are used for large scale municipal supplies.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Particularly important are distillation (desalination of seawater) and reverse osmosis.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Bringing water to its boiling point (about 100 °C or 212 °F at sea level), is the oldest and most effective method of sterilising water since it eliminates most microbes causing intestinal disease, but it cannot remove chemical toxins or impurities.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] For human health, complete sterilisation of water is not required, since heat resistant microbes do not affect intestines.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The traditional advice of boiling water for ten minutes is mainly for additional safety, since microbes start expiring at temperatures greater than 60 °C (140 °F).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Though the boiling point decreases with increasing altitude, it is not enough to affect disinfection.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In areas where the water is "hard" (that is, containing significant dissolved calcium salts), boiling decomposes the bicarbonate ions, resulting in partial precipitation as calcium carbonate.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This is the "fur" that builds up on kettle elements, etc., in hard water areas.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] With the exception of calcium, boiling does not remove solutes of higher boiling point than water and in fact increases their concentration (due to some water being lost as vapour).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Boiling does not leave a residual disinfectant in the water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Therefore, water that is boiled and then stored for any length of time may acquire new pathogens.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Granular activated carbon is a form of activated carbon with a high surface area.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] It adsorbs many compounds including many toxic compounds.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Water passing through activated carbon is commonly used in municipal regions with organic contamination, taste or odors.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Many household water filters and fish tanks use activated carbon filters to purify water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Household filters for drinking water sometimes contain silver as metallic silver nanoparticle.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] If water is held in the carbon block for longer periods, microorganisms can grow inside which results in fouling and contamination.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Silver nanoparticles are excellent anti-bacterial material and can decompose toxic halo-organic compounds such as pesticides into non-toxic organic products.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Filtered water must be used soon after it is filtered, as the low amount of remaining microbes may proliferate over time.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In general, these home filters remove over 90% of the chlorine in a glass of treated water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] These filters must be periodically replaced otherwise the bacterial content of the water may actually increase due to the growth of bacteria within the filter unit.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Distillation involves boiling water to produce water vapour.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The vapour contacts a cool surface where it condenses as a liquid.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Because the solutes are not normally vaporised, they remain in the boiling solution.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Even distillation does not completely purify water, because of contaminants with similar boiling points and droplets of unvapourised liquid carried with the steam.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] However, 99.9% pure water can be obtained by distillation.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Direct contact membrane distillation (DCMD) passes heated seawater along the surface of a hydrophobic polymer membrane.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Evaporated water passes from the hot side through pores in the membrane forming a stream of cold pure water on the other side.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The difference in vapour pressure between the hot and cold side helps to push water molecules through.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Reverse osmosis involves mechanical pressure applied to force water through a semi-permeable membrane.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Contaminants are left on the other side of the membrane.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Reverse osmosis is theoretically the most thorough method of large scale water purification available, although perfect semi-permeable membranes are difficult to create.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Unless membranes are well-maintained, algae and other life forms can colonise the membranes.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Carbon dioxide or other low molecular weight gas can be mixed with contaminated water at high pressure and low temperature to exothermically form gas hydrate crystals.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Hydrate may be separated by centrifuge or sedimentation.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Water can be released from the hydrate crystals by heating.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Bioremediation uses microorganisms to remove waste products from a contaminated area.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Since 1991 bioremediation has been a suggested tactic to remove impurities such as alkanes, perchlorates, and metals.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Bioremediation has seen success because perchlorates are highly soluble, making them difficult to remove.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Example applications of *Dechloromonas agitata* strain CKB include field studies conducted in Maryland and the US Southwest.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Hydrogen peroxide (H 2O 2) is a common disinfectant that can purify water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] It is typically produced at chemical plants and transported to the contaminated water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] An alternative approach employs a gold-palladium catalyst to synthesize H 2O 2 from ambient hydrogen and oxygen atoms at the use site.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The latter was reported to be faster and 107 times more potent at killing *Escherichia coli* than commercial H 2O 2, and over 108 times more effective than chlorine.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The catalytic reaction also produces reactive oxygen species (ROS) that bind and degrade other compounds.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Many municipalities have moved from using free chlorine, to chloramine as a disinfection agent.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] However, chloramine appears to be a corrosive agent in some water systems.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Chloramine can dissolve the "protective" film inside older service lines, leading to the leaching of lead into residential spigots.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This can result in harmful exposure, including elevated blood lead levels.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Adding orthophosphate as an anticorrosive agent has been effective in reducing lead levels in drinking water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Distillation removes all minerals from water, and the membrane methods of reverse osmosis and nanofiltration remove most to all minerals.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This results in demineralised water which is not considered ideal drinking water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The World Health Organization has investigated the health effects of demineralised water since 1980.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Experiments in humans found that demineralised water increased diuresis and the elimination of electrolytes, with decreased blood serum potassium concentration.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Magnesium, calcium, and other minerals in water can help to protect against nutritional deficiency.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Demineralized water may also increase the risk from toxic metals because it more readily leaches materials from piping like lead and cadmium, which is prevented by dissolved minerals such as calcium and magnesium.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Low-mineral water has been implicated in specific cases of lead poisoning in infants, when lead from pipes leached at especially high rates into the water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Recommendations for magnesium have been put at a minimum of 10 mg/L with 20–30 mg/L optimum; for calcium a 20 mg/L minimum and a 40–80 mg/L optimum, and a total water hardness (adding magnesium and calcium) of 2 to 4 mmol/L.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] At water hardness above 5 mmol/L, higher incidence of gallstones, kidney stones, urinary stones, arthrosis, and arthropathies have been observed.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Additionally, desalination processes can increase the risk of bacterial contamination.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Manufacturers of home water distillers claim the opposite—that minerals in water are the cause of many diseases, and that most beneficial minerals come from food, not water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The first experiments into water filtration were made in the 17th century.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Sir Francis Bacon attempted to desalinate sea water by passing the flow through a sand filter.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Although his experiment did not succeed, it marked the beginning of a new interest in the field.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The fathers of microscopy, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek and Robert Hooke, used the newly invented microscope to observe for the first time small material particles that lay suspended in the water, laying the groundwork for the future understanding of waterborne pathogens.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The first documented use of sand filters to purify the water supply dates to 1804, when the owner of a bleachery in Paisley, Scotland, John Gibb, installed an experimental filter, selling his unwanted surplus to the public.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This method was refined in the following two decades by engineers working for private water companies, and it culminated in the first treated public water supply in the world, installed by engineer James Simpson for the Chelsea Waterworks Company in London in 1829.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This installation provided filtered water for every resident of the area, and the network design was widely copied throughout the United Kingdom in the ensuing decades.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The practice of water treatment soon became mainstream and common, and the virtues of the system were made starkly apparent after the investigations of the physician John Snow during the 1854 Broad Street cholera outbreak.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Snow was sceptical of the then-dominant miasma theory that stated that diseases were caused by noxious "bad airs".
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Although the germ theory of disease had not yet been developed, Snow's observations led him to discount the prevailing theory.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] His data convinced the local council to disable the water pump, which promptly ended the outbreak.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The Metropolis Water Act introduced the regulation of the water supply companies in London, including minimum standards of water quality for the first time.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The Act "made provision for securing the supply to the Metropolis of pure and wholesome water", and required that all water be "effectually filtered" from 31 December 1855.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This was followed up with legislation for the mandatory inspection of water quality, including comprehensive chemical analyses, in 1858.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This legislation set a worldwide precedent for similar state public health interventions across Europe.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The Metropolitan Commission of Sewers was formed at the same time, water filtration was adopted throughout the country, and new water intakes on the Thames were established above Teddington Lock.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Automatic pressure filters, where the water is forced under pressure through the filtration system, were innovated in 1899 in England.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] By the 1920s large municipal water systems installed rapid sand filters, which require smaller land areas compared to slow sand filters.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] John Snow was the first to successfully use chlorine to disinfect the water supply in Soho that had helped spread the cholera outbreak.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] William Soper also used chlorinated lime to treat the sewage produced by typhoid patients in 1879.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] In a paper published in 1894, Moritz Traube formally proposed the addition of chloride of lime (calcium hypochlorite) to water to render it "germ-free".
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Two other investigators confirmed Traube's findings and published their papers in 1895.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Early attempts at implementing water chlorination at a water treatment plant were made in 1893 in Hamburg, Germany and in 1897 the city of Maidstone, England was the first to have its entire water supply treated with chlorine.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Permanent water chlorination began in 1905, when a faulty slow sand filter and a contaminated water supply led to a serious typhoid fever epidemic in Lincoln, England.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Alexander Cruickshank Houston used chlorination of the water to stem the epidemic.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] His installation fed a concentrated solution of chloride of lime to the water being treated.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The chlorination of the water supply helped stop the epidemic and as a precaution, the chlorination was continued until 1911 when a new water supply was instituted.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The first continuous use of chlorine in the United States for disinfection took place in 1908 at Boonton Reservoir (on the Rockaway River), which served as the supply for Jersey City, New Jersey.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Chlorination was achieved by controlled additions of dilute solutions of chloride of lime (calcium hypochlorite) at doses of 0.2 to 0.35 ppm.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The treatment process was conceived by John L.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Leal and the chlorination plant was designed by George Warren Fuller.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Over the next few years, chlorine disinfection using chloride of lime were rapidly installed in drinking water systems around the world.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The technique of purification of drinking water by use of compressed liquefied chlorine gas was developed by a British officer in the Indian Medical Service, Vincent B.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Army Major Carl Rogers Darnall, Professor of Chemistry at the Army Medical School, gave the first practical demonstration of this in 1910.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Lyster of the Army Medical Department used a solution of calcium hypochlorite in a linen bag to treat water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] For many decades, Lyster's method remained the standard for U.S. ground forces in the field and in camps, implemented in the form of the familiar Lyster Bag (also spelled Lister Bag).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The bag was made of canvas and could hold 36 gallons of water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] It was porous and held up by ropes, purifying water with the help of calcium hypochlorite solution.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Each bag had a faucet attached, which was used to flush water for testing, as well as dispensing for use.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] This became the basis for present day systems of municipal water *purification*.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The WHO estimates that 94% of these diarrhoeal disease cases are preventable through modifications to the environment, including access to safe water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Simple techniques for treating water at home, such as chlorination, filters, and solar disinfection, and for storing it in safe containers could save a huge number of lives each year.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Reducing deaths from waterborne diseases is a major public health goal in developing countries.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] The global water purification market is worth 22 billion dollars.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-purification] Home water filters and purifiers in India are common.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Advanced water treatment methods have been developed in recent decades due to increased concerns about new pollutants like microplastics, pharmaceuticals, and per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] These include advanced oxidation processes, membrane filtration, and adsorption-based techniques utilizing materials like tailored nanomaterials and activated carbon.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Additionally, energy efficiency, resource recovery, and sustainability in water treatment systems are receiving more attention, especially in areas where water is scarce and environmental demands are growing.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Water contamination is primarily caused by the discharge of untreated wastewater from industrial and commercial activities.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] The effluent from various enterprises, which contains varying levels of contaminants, is dumped into rivers or other water resources.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] The wastewater may have a high proportion of organic and inorganic contaminants at the initial discharge.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Industries generate wastewater as a result of fabrication processes, processes dealing with paper and pulp, textiles, chemicals, and from various streams such as cooling towers, boilers, and production lines.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Treatment for drinking water production involves the removal of contaminants and/or inactivation of any potentially harmful microbes from raw water to produce water that is pure enough for human consumption without any short term or long term risk of any adverse health effect.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] In general terms, the greatest microbial risks are associated with ingestion of water that is contaminated with human or animal (including bird) feces.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Feces can be a source of pathogenic bacteria, viruses, protozoa and helminths.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] The removal or destruction of microbial pathogens is essential, and commonly involves the use of reactive chemical agents such as suspended solids, to remove bacteria, algae, viruses, fungi, and minerals including iron and manganese.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Research including Professor Linda Lawton's group at Robert Gordon University, Aberdeen is working to improve detection of cyanobacteria.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] These substances continue to cause great harm to several less developed countries who do not have access to effective water purification systems.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Measures taken to ensure water quality not only relate to the treatment of the water, but to its conveyance and distribution after treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] It is therefore common practice to keep residual disinfectants in the treated water to kill bacteriological contamination during distribution and to keep the pipes clean.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Water supplied to domestic properties such as for tap water or other uses, may be further treated before use, often using an in-line treatment process.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Such treatments can include water softening or ion exchange.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Wastewater treatment is a process which removes contaminants from wastewater.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] The resulting effluent, discharged to a water body, has an acceptable impact on the environment.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Domestic wastewater, also called municipal wastewater or sewage, is processed at a sewage treatment plant.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Industrial wastewater is often processed at a specially-designed industrial wastewater treatment facility, or at a sewage treatment plant.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] In the latter case the industry typically performs on-site pretreatment of the waste, before it is sent to the municipal plant.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Other types of wastewater treatment plants include agricultural wastewater treatment and leachate treatment plants.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] The term "wastewater treatment" is often used to mean "sewage treatment".
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Common processes in wastewater treatment include phase separation, such as sedimentation, various biological and chemical processes, such as oxidation, and polishing.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] The main by-product from wastewater treatment plants is a type of sludge that is usually treated in the same or another wastewater treatment plant.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Biogas can be another by-product if the process uses anaerobic treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Water treatment is used to reduce impact on equipment used in industrial processes, such as heating, cooling, processing, cleaning, and rinsing so that operating costs and risks are reduced.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Poor water treatment lets water interact with the surfaces of pipes and vessels which contain it.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Steam boilers can scale up or corrode, and these deposits will mean more fuel is needed to heat the same amount of water.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Cooling towers can also scale up and corrode, but left untreated, the warm, dirty water they can contain will encourage bacteria to grow, and Legionnaires' disease can be the fatal consequence.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] Water treatment is also used to improve the quality of water contacting the manufactured product (e.g., semiconductors) and/or can be part of the product (e.g., beverages, pharmaceuticals).
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] In these instances, poor water treatment can cause defective products.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] In many cases, effluent water from one process can be suitable for reuse in another process if given suitable treatment.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] This can reduce costs by lowering charges for water consumption, reduce the costs of effluent disposal because of reduced volume, and lower energy costs due to the recovery of heat in recycled wastewater.
[src:water-treatment-control/water-treatment] For the elimination of hazardous chemicals from the water, many treatment procedures have been applied.
